Audiobook awards]]\n[[Category:American literary awards]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1996]]\n[[Category:1996 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Section heading change: Infrequent Award Categories \u2192 Infrequent award categories using ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Audie_Award"}
{"title_page": "Michelle Malkin", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Michele Merkin}}\n{{short description|American author and  journalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2018}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Michelle Malkin\n| image              = Michelle Malkin 2008 2.jpg\n| birth_name         = Michelle Maglalang\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1970|10|20}}<ref name=\"nahm\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Oberlin College]]\n| occupation         = Author, [[Print syndication|syndicated]] [[columnist]], [[television personality]], and [[blog]]ger, [[Fox News]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Jesse Malkin|1993}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|michellemalkin.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Michelle Malkin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|l|k|\u026a|n}}; n\u00e9e '''Maglalang'''; born October 20, 1970) is an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] blogger, political commentator, author and businesswoman. Her weekly [[Print syndication|syndicated]] [[column (newspaper)|column]] appears in a number of newspapers and websites.<ref name=\"pitts\">[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2008-03-09/news/0803080095_1_michelle-malkin-moonbats-daughter \"Right at home\" Pitts, Jonathan.] ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''<span>, March 9, 2008, page E 1.</span></ref> She was a [[Fox News]] contributor and has been a guest on [[MSNBC]], [[C-SPAN]], and national radio programs. Malkin has written four books published by [[Regnery Publishing]]. She founded the conservative websites [[Twitchy]] and ''[[Hot Air]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/12/michelle-malkin-laughs-liberal-tweets-all-way-bank/355984/ | title = Michelle Malkin Laughs at Liberal Tweets All the Way to the Bank | last = Bump | first = Philip | date = December 10, 2013 | work = The Atlantic|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Amanda Carpenter]] has reported that Malkin began to \"link arms with the most vocal elements of the white nationalist movement\" in 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://thebulwark.com/michelle-malkin-mother-of-groypers/|title=Michelle Malkin: Mother of Groypers|date=2020-03-09|website=The Bulwark|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Malkin faced criticism for her association with white nationalists and neo-Nazis, including [[Nick Fuentes]] and [[Identity Evropa]]. In February 2020, she was dropped by conservative organization [[Young America's Foundation]] (YAF) due to her support of Holocaust deniers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/American-Politics/Michelle-Malkin-shunned-by-conservatives-over-support-for-antisemites-608349|title=Michelle Malkin shunned by conservatives over support for antisemites|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/politics/conservatives-blast-michelle-malkins-anti-semitic-questions-once-admired-her-this-is-disgusting/|title=Conservatives Blast Michelle Malkin on 'Anti-Semitic' Questions|date=2020-03-03|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMichelle Malkin was born October 20, 1970<ref name=\"nahm\" /> in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], to [[Philippine nationality law|Philippine citizens]] Rafaela (n\u00e9e Perez) \u2013 a homemaker and teacher \u2013 and Apolo DeCastro Maglalang, who was then a physician-in-training.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Several months prior to Malkin's birth, her parents had immigrated to the United States on an employer-sponsored visa.<ref name=\"lamb\">{{cite web | author = Lamb, Brian | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071013191746/http://booknotes.org/Transcript/?ProgramID=1705 | archivedate = October 13, 2007|url-status=dead | title = Booknotes Transcript on \"Invasion: How America Still Welcomes Terrorists\" | work = [[Booknotes]] | publisher = C-SPAN | url = http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/173558-1/Michelle+Malkin.aspx}}</ref> After her father finished his medical training, the family moved<ref>{{cite web | title = In Depth | publisher = Book TV | date = January 3, 2011 | url = http://www.c-span.org/video/?291010-1/depth-michelle-malkin}}</ref> to [[Absecon, New Jersey]]. Malkin has a younger brother.<ref name=\"MM\">{{cite web | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2004/12/03/maglalangadingdoing-this/ | title = Maglalangadingdong this | publisher = MichelleMalkin.com | author = Malkin, Michelle | date = December 3, 2004 | accessdate = May 24, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She has described her parents as [[Ronald Reagan]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] who were \"not incredibly politically active\".<ref name=\"nahm\">Nahm, H Y. [http://www.goldsea.com/Personalities/Malkin/malkin.html \"Michelle Malkin: The Radical Right's Asian Pitbull\"], \"Goldsea Asian American\". Retrieved July 16, 2009.</ref>\n\nMalkin, a [[Roman Catholic]],<ref name=\"nahm\"/><ref>Malkin, Michelle, (April 9, 2010), [http://michellemalkin.com/2010/04/09/the-pfleger-ization-of-the-catholic-church/ \"The Pfleger-ization of the Catholic Church\"], MichelleMalkin.com, April 9, 2010. Retrieved August 17, 2011.</ref> attended [[Holy Spirit High School (New Jersey)|Holy Spirit Roman Catholic High School]], where she edited the school newspaper and aspired to become a concert [[pianist]].<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Following her graduation in 1988, she enrolled at [[Oberlin College]].<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Malkin had planned to pursue a [[bachelor's degree]] in music, but changed her major to English.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> During her college years, she worked as a press inserter, tax preparation aide, and network news librarian.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/personalities/michelle-malkin/bio/#s=m-q | title = On Air Personalities: Michelle Malkin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110818050151/http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/personalities/michelle-malkin/bio/#s=m-q |archive-date=August 18, 2011 | work = Fox News | access-date = August 18, 2011}}</ref> Her first article for the paper heavily criticized Oberlin's [[affirmative action]] program and received a \"hugely negative response\" from other students on campus.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> She graduated in 1992<ref name=\"bookshelf\">[http://www.oberlin.edu/alummag/spring2003/bookshelf.html Bookshelf: Invasion By Michelle Malkin], Reviewed by Jan Ting, ''Oberlin Alumni Magazine'', Spring 2003. Retrieved August 18, 2011.</ref> and later described her ''alma mater'' as \"radically left-wing\".<ref name=\"goliath\">Article preview. [https://web.archive.org/web/20080319092906/http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0199-5264457_ITM \"Michelle Malkin\"], ''[[The American Enterprise]]'', September 1, 2005. Retrieved on March 4, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Journalism===\n[[File:Michelle Malkin by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Malkin speaking in South Carolina in 2016]]\nMalkin began her journalism career at the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'', working as a columnist from 1992 to 1994. In 1995, she worked in [[Washington, D.C.]] as a journalism fellow at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.foxnews.com/bios/talent/michelle-malkin/ | title = Michelle Malkin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090819151619/http://www.foxnews.com/bios/talent/michelle-malkin | archive-date=August 19, 2009 | work = FoxNews.com | access-date = July 23, 2009}}</ref> a free-market, anti-government regulation, [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] [[think tank]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/05/AR2009030503293.html | title = Europe Advises U.S. Officials on Climate | first1 = Juliet | last1 = Eilperin | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] | date = March 6, 2009}}</ref> In 1996, she moved to [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], where she wrote columns for ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. Malkin became a nationally [[print syndication|syndicated]] columnist with [[Creators Syndicate]] in 1999.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.html \"Michelle Malkin's Latest Opinion Column HLML\"], [[Creators Syndicate]]</ref><ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.rss \"Michelle Malkin's Latest Opinion Column RSS\"], [[Creators Syndicate]].</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2006, ''[[Hot Air]]'', a \"conservative Internet broadcast network\", went into operation, with Malkin as founder/CEO.<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/4/prweb376471.htm \"Conservative Internet Broadcast Network Debuts\"], [[PR Web]], April 24, 2006, Accessed July 18, 2009</ref> The site's staff at launch included [[Allahpundit]] and Bryan Preston. Preston was replaced by [[Ed Morrissey]] on February 25, 2008.<ref>Morrissey, Ed.[http://www.captainsquartersblog.com/mt/archives/017106.php \"The Road Goes Ever On\"] February 25, 2008</ref> In February 2010, Hotair.com was bought by [[Salem Communications]] and is no longer administered by Malkin.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2010/02/21/a-note-on-the-acquisition-of-hot-air/ \"A note on the acquisition of Hot Air\"] February 21, 2010</ref>\n\nFor years, Malkin was a frequent commentator for [[Fox News]] and a regular guest host of ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]''. In 2007, she announced that she would not return to ''The O'Reilly Factor'', claiming that Fox News had mishandled a dispute over derogatory statements made about her by [[Geraldo Rivera]] in a ''[[The Boston Globe|Boston Globe]]'' interview.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/09/01/geraldo-rivera-unhinged \"Geraldo Rivera unhinged\"], MichelleMalkin.com, September 1, 2007.</ref> Since 2007, she has concentrated on her writing, blogging, and public speaking, although she still appears on television occasionally, especially with [[Sean Hannity#Television|Sean Hannity]] and formerly with [[Greta Van Susteren]] on Fox News and ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' once a week.\n\nMalkin had been a contributor to [[Conservative Review|CRTV]], but left the network following its merger with [[TheBlaze]] in December 2018 and joined competitor [[Newsmax TV]].<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Swanson | first1 = Ian | title = Michelle Malkin departs CRTV one day after Blaze merger announced | url = https://thehill.com/homenews/media/419677-michelle-malkin-departs-crtv-one-day-after-blaze-merger-announced | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = TheHill | date = December 4, 2018 | language = en}}</ref>\n\nMalkin also founded the website [[Twitchy]], a [[Twitter]] [[content curation]] site.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://twitchy.com/about/ | title = About Us | work = Twitchy | access-date = September 4, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130806095639/http://twitchy.com/about/ | archive-date = August 6, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nA day after the death of journalist [[Cokie Roberts]], Malkin claimed that Cokie was \"One of the first Guilty Culprits of Fake News\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/michelle-malkin-smears-cokie-roberts-on-the-day-of-her-death-one-of-the-first-guilty-culprits-of-fake-news | title = Michelle Malkin Smears Cokie Roberts on the Day of Her Death: 'One of the First Guilty Culprits of Fake News' | last = Baragona | first = Justin | date = September 18, 2019|access-date=September 19, 2019 | language = en}}</ref>  [[Brian Stelter]] quickly said, during the panel discussion, \"You're attacking her today.  I just want to be clear: the body isn't even cold yet.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Books===\nMalkin has written a total of seven books.\n\nHer first book, ''[[Invasion: How America Still Welcomes Terrorists, Criminals, and Other Foreign Menaces]]'' (2002)<ref>[[Regnery Publishing]], 2002, {{ISBN|0-89526-075-1}}</ref> was a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestseller]].\n\nIn 2004, she wrote ''[[In Defense of Internment|In Defense of Internment: The Case for 'Racial Profiling' in World War II and the War on Terror]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Malkin|first=Michelle|title=In Defense of Internment: The Case for 'Racial Profiling' in World War II and the War on Terror|url=https://archive.org/details/indefen_mal_2004_00_5055|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=Regnery Publishing|isbn=978-0-89526-051-2}}</ref> defending the U.S. government's [[Japanese American internment|internment]] of 112,000 Japanese Americans in prison camps during [[World War II]], and arguing that the same procedures could be used on [[Arab people|Arab]]- and [[Muslim]]-Americans today. The book engendered harsh criticism from several [[Asian American]] civil rights organizations.<ref name=\"imdiversity2004\">{{Cite press release | publisher = Japanese American citizens League | url = http://www.imdiversity.com/Villages/asian/politics_law/archives/jacl_malkin_response_0804.asp | title = JACL Responds to \"Defense of Internment, Case for Race Profiling\" | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081007095519/http://www.imdiversity.com/villages/asian/politics_law/archives/jacl_malkin_response_0804.asp | archive-date=October 7, 2008 | website = IMdiversity.com | date = August 24, 2004 | access-date = July 18, 2009}}</ref> The Historians' Committee for Fairness, an organization of scholars and professional researchers, condemned the book for not having undergone [[peer review]] and argued that its central thesis is false.<ref>Historians' Committee for Fairness. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070805083832/http://hnn.us/readcomment.php?id=40982 \"Open Letter to Michelle Malkin\"] [[History News Network]], August 31, 2004. (archived from [http://hnn.us/readcomment.php?id=40982 the original] on August 5, 2007).</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = In disgrace or in defense? | first = Douglas | last = Brown | work = Denver Post. | date = September 2, 2004 | page = F.01}}</ref> As a result of the controversy, the Hawaii-based newspaper ''[[MidWeek]]'' dropped her column in August 2004;<ref>{{cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2004/08/27/book-buzz-2/ | title = Book Buzz | publisher = michellemalkin.com | date = August 27, 2004}}</ref> ''[[The Virginian-Pilot]]'' called her \"an Asian [[Ann Coulter]]\" and dropped her column in November 2004.<ref>Editor & Publisher Staff.[https://web.archive.org/web/20050312041405/http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000724900 \"Virginia Paper Drops Columnist Malkin\"], ''[[Editor and Publisher]]'', November 22, 2004. Retrieved July 18, 2009.</ref> Malkin responded: \"I'm not Asian, I'm American\", and described the comparison to Coulter as \"a compliment\".<ref>{{Cite web | last1 = Malzberg | first1 = Steve | url = http://www.newsmax.com/archives/ic/2004/11/28/124846.shtml | title = Malkin - Liberal Bigotry on the Rise | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20050406145048/http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2004/11/28/124846.shtml | archive-date=April 6, 2005 | work = [[NewsMax Media|NewsMax.com]] | date = November 28, 2004}}</ref>\n\nMalkin's third book, ''Unhinged: Exposing Liberals Gone Wild'', was released in October 2005.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Unhinged: Exposing Liberals Gone Wild | publisher = Regnery Publishing | date = 2005 | isbn = 0-89526-030-1 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/unhingedexposing00malk }}</ref>\n\n''[[Culture of Corruption: Obama and His Team of Tax Cheats, Crooks, and Cronies]]'', Malkin's fourth book, was released in July 2009<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Regnery Publishing | date = 2009 | isbn = 978-1-59698-109-6 | title = Culture of Corruption: Obama and His Team of Tax Cheats, Crooks, and Cronies}}</ref> and was a ''The New York Times'' Non-Fiction, Hardcover Best Seller for six weeks.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Sept. 20, 2009 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/20/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html?_r=1&ref=bestseller | access-date = October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"malkin080509\">Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2009/08/05/culture-of-corruption-hits-1-thank-you/ \"Lead Story: Culture of Corruption hits #1: Thank you!\"], michellemalkin.com, August 5, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Dixler | first = Elsa | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/16/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html | title = August 16, 2009 Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = August 16, 2009 | access-date = May 8, 2012}}</ref> Malkin said she hoped the book would \"shatter completely the myths of hope and change in the new politics in Washington\", described the Obama administration as run by \"influence peddlers, power brokers and very wealthy people\", and called it \"one of the most corrupt administrations in recent memory\".<ref name=\"hannityshow\">Malkin, Michelle.[http://www.foxnews.com/video2/video08.html?maven_referralObject=7441258&maven_referralPlaylistId=&sRevUrl=http://www.foxnews.com/hannity/index.html \"Interview on the Sean Hannity Show\"],\"Fox News Channel\", FoxNews.com, July 27, 2009. Retrieved July 29, 2009.</ref> She later discussed chapter two of the book, \"Bitter Half: First Crony Michelle Obama\", on [[Today (NBC program)|NBC's ''Today'' show]]. She described [[Michelle Obama]] as \"steeped in the politics of the [[Daley family|Daley machine]]\", and as having based her professional career on nepotism and \"old white boy\" network connections.<ref>{{cite video | url = http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26184891/vp/32200089#32200089 | title = Today show | format = Flash | people = Matt Lauer, Michelle Malkin | date = July 29, 2009 | publisher = NBC News | medium = Television production | accessdate = July 29, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n''Who Built That: Awe-Inspiring Stories of American Tinkerpreneurs'', released May 2015,<ref>{{cite book | author = Michelle Malkin | title = Who Built That: Awe-Inspiring Stories of American Tinkerpreneurs | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zA9DCQAAQBAJ | date = May 19, 2015 | publisher = Simon and Schuster | isbn = 978-1-4767-8494-6}}</ref> presents stories of American inventors and business people, directly challenging the \"[[you didn't build that]]\" statement made by President [[Barack Obama]] on July 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | last = Bedard | first = Paul | title = Michelle Malkin's 'Who Built That' storms onto bestseller list | url = http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-malkins-who-built-that-storms-onto-bestseller-list/article/2565114 | newspaper = Washington Examiner | date = May 27, 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}<br />{{cite news | last = Lozado | first = Carlos | title = Michelle Malkin's new book has a chapter in which she pretends to be a roll of toilet paper | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/book-party/wp/2015/06/03/michelle-malkins-new-book-has-a-chapter-in-which-she-pretends-to-be-a-roll-of-toilet-paper/ | newspaper = Washington post | date = June 3, 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Sold Out (book)|''Sold Out: How High-Tech Billionaires & Bipartisan Beltway Crapweasels Are Screwing America's Best & Brightest Workers'']], M. Malkin and J. Miano, [[Simon & Schuster]] Audio/Mercury Ink (November 10, 2015)\n\n''Open Borders Inc.: Who's Funding America's Destruction?'' Michelle Malkin, [[Regnery Publishing]] (September 10, 2019)\n\n==Blogging==\n\nIn June 2004, Malkin launched a political blog, MichelleMalkin.com.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2004/06/08/extreme-makeover/ \"Extreme Makeover\"], \"MichelleMalkin.com\", June 8, 2004.</ref> A 2007 memo from the [[National Republican Senatorial Committee]] described Malkin as one of the five \"best-read national conservative bloggers\",<ref>Budoff, Carrie. [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0607/4483.html \"GOP issues rules to avoid Macaca moments\"], ''[[The Politico]]'', June 13, 2007</ref> and as of 2012 [[Technorati]] had ranked MichelleMalkin.com in its \"Top 100 blogs of all types\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://technorati.com/search?q=michelle&return=sites | title = Blogs relating to \"michelle\" (4 blogs found out of 1187182) | publisher = Technorati.com | date =  | accessdate = May 8, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2011, the people search company [[PeekYou]] claimed that Malkin had the largest digital footprint of any political blogger.<ref>{{cite web | author = PeekYou Team | url = http://score.peekyou.com/the-peekscores-of-30-top-political-bloggers/ | title = The PeekScores of 30 Top Political Bloggers | publisher = score.peekyou.com | date = November 30, 2011 | accessdate = May 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528124319/http://score.peekyou.com/the-peekscores-of-30-top-political-bloggers/ |archive-date=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMalkin accused hip hop artist [[Akon]] of degrading women in a ''HotAir'' YouTube video in May 2007. Following this, Akon's record label, [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG), issued a [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act|DMCA]] takedown notice removing the video.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://www.michellemalkin.com/archives/007446.htm | title = Akon's record company abuses DMCA to stifle criticism on YouTube | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070505053513/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007446.htm | archive-date=May 5, 2007 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = May 3, 2007}}</ref> UMG retracted the notice after the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] joined Malkin in contesting the removal as a misuse of copyright law.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007514.htm | title = UMG & YouTube retreat over Akon report | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = May 14, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070516041140/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007514.htm | archive-date=May 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Universal Music Group Backs Off Claims to Michelle Malkin Video | url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2007/05/universal-music-group-backs-claims-michelle-malkin-video | website = Electronic Frontier Foundation | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | language = en | date = May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nMichelleMalkin.com was revamped and moved to a larger server on [[WordPress]] in  June 2007.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/06/19/welcome-to-the-new-michellemalkincom \"Welcome to the new michellemalkin.com!\"],\"MichelleMalkin.com\", June 19, 2007.</ref>\n\nMalkin has also been a contributor to anti-immigration website [[VDARE]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-08-14/alt-right-charlottesville-daily-stormer-racism-white-supremacists | title = Op-Ed: White supremacist publications took a hit after Charlottesville. Now they're stronger than ever | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jamil Hussein===\n{{Main|Jamil Hussein controversy}}\nMalkin was among the first of several bloggers who questioned the credibility and even the existence of Iraqi police Captain \"Jamil Hussein\" who had been used as a source by the [[Associated Press]] in over 60 stories about the Iraq war. The controversy started in November 2006 when the AP reported that six Iraqis had been burned alive as they left a mosque and that four mosques had been destroyed, citing Hussein as one of its sources. In January 2007, Malkin visited Baghdad, and stated, \"the Iraqi Ministry of Interior says disputed Associated Press source Jamil Hussein does exist. At least one story he told the AP just doesn't check out: The Sunni mosques that as Hussein claimed and AP reported as 'destroyed,' 'torched' and 'burned and blown up' are all still standing. So the credibility of every AP story relying on Jamil Hussein remains dubious.\"<ref name=malkin20070121>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/01/21/fact-checking-the-ap-and-jamil-hussein/ \"Fact-checking the AP and Jamil Hussein\"], MichelleMalkin.com, January 21, 2007.</ref> Malkin has since issued a correction for her denial of Hussein's existence, \"I relayed information from multiple sources\u2014CPATT, Centcom, and two other military sources on the ground in Iraq\u2014that the Associated Press's disputed source, Jamil Hussein, could not be found.\" [...] \"I regret the error,\" but still contested AP claims of destroyed mosques and civilians burned alive.<ref name=malkin20070121 /><ref name=MM6641>{{cite web | author = Malkin, Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/006641.htm | title = Corrections | date = March 4, 2016 | quote = I relayed information from multiple sources--CPATT, Centcom, and two other military sources on the ground in Iraq-- that the Associated Press's disputed source, Jamil Hussein, could not be found. As I noted on the 4th, the AP reported that the Ministry of Interior in Iraq has now said a Captain Jamil Hussein does work in the al Khadra police station. I regret the error. But no blogger should apologize for raising legitimate questions about AP's transparency, its reliance on local foreign stringers of dubious origins, and information that sources such as Hussein have provided the AP. I will continue to pursue some of the unresolved issues related to this. |url-status=unfit | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070217113609/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/006641.htm | archivedate = February 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Students Against War controversy===\nIn April 2006, Students Against War (SAW), a campus group at [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], staged a protest against the presence of military recruiters on campus, and sent out a [[press release]] containing contact details (names, phone numbers and e-mail addresses) of three student leaders for use by reporters. Malkin included these contact details in a blog column entitled \"Seditious Santa Cruz vs. America\".<ref name=MM04974>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004974.htm | title = Seditious Santa Cruz vs. America | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419062349/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004974.htm | archive-date=April 19, 2006 | website = michellemalkin.com | date = April 12, 2006}}</ref> Malkin claimed the contact information was originally taken from SAW's own website, but that later SAW had removed it and had \"wiped\" the \"cached version\".<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004999.htm | title = More Thuggery In Santa Cruz | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080720033805/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004999.htm | archive-date=July 20, 2008 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = April 17, 2006}}</ref> The students asked Malkin to remove the contact details from her blog, but Malkin reposted them several times<ref name=\"sentinel\">{{Cite web | author = Sentinel | url = http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2006/04/22/18170531.php | title = Malkin moves, takes child from school, as SC students retaliate | work = Santa Cruz Indymedia | date = April 22, 2006 | access-date = July 20, 2009}}</ref> writing in her blog: \"I am leaving it up. If you are contacting them, I do not condone death threats or foul language. As for SAW, my message is this: You are responsible for your individual actions. Other individuals are responsible for theirs. Grow up and take responsibility.\"<ref name=MM04974/>\n\nSAW remarked: \"Due to the continued irresponsible actions of some bloggers, members of the group have received numerous death threats and anti-Semitic comments through phone calls and emails.\"<ref name=\"students\">\nStudents Against The War. [http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2006/04/19/18164431.php \"Far-Right Threats Fail to Distract from Santa Cruz Protest Successes\"], April 19, 2006,</ref> A blog war ensued. Malkin claimed that she received hostile e-mails,<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/005008.htm | title = The Moonbats Strike Back | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060503030350/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/005008.htm | archive-date=May 3, 2006 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = April 17, 2006}}</ref> then her private home address, phone number, photos of her neighborhood and maps to her house were published on several websites. The ''[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]'' reported receiving an email from Malkin saying that this forced her to remove one of her children from school and move her family.<ref>{{cite web | author = Sideman, Roger | url = http://www.scsextra.com/story.php?sid=37840 | title = Cyber war over UCSC protest heats up | work = [[Santa Cruz Sentinel]] | date = April 22, 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120306162152/http://www.scsextra.com/story.php?sid=37840 | archivedate = March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnother controversy involving private addresses began on July 1, 2006, when Malkin and other bloggers commented on a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' Travel section article that had featured the town where Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] and Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] owned summer homes. The article included a picture of Rumsfeld's long tree-lined driveway that showed a birdhouse and small portion of the housefront.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Kilborn | first = Peter T. | url = http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/06/30/travel/escapes/30michaels.html?ex=1309320000&en=538a0c0e85134892&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | title = Weekends with the President's Men | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070906114610/http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/06/30/travel/escapes/30michaels.html?ex=1309320000&en=538a0c0e85134892&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | archive-date=September 6, 2007 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = June 30, 2006}}</ref> Malkin declared that this story was part of \"a concerted, organized effort to dig up and publicize the private home information of prominent conservatives in the media and blogosphere to intimidate them.\" The photos of Rumsfeld's house were taken with Rumsfeld's permission.<ref>{{cite web | last = Greenwald | first = Glenn | url = http://glenngreenwald.blogspot.com/2006/07/what-is-left-of-malkin-hinderaker-and.html | title = What is left of Malkin, Hinderaker and Horowitz's credibility? | publisher = Unclaimed Territory | date = July 3, 2006 | accessdate = May 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\n===Immigration===\nMalkin opposes [[birthright citizenship in the United States|birthright citizenship]] to U.S.-born children of foreign tourists, temporary foreign workers, and [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]]. She claims this undermines the integrity of citizenship and national security, and argues that the [[Citizenship Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment to the Constitution]], \"originally intended to ensure the citizenship rights of newly freed slaves and their families after the Civil War, has evolved into a magnet for alien lawbreakers and a shield for terrorist infiltrators and enemy combatants\".<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin070403.asp \"What makes an American?\"], ''[[Jewish World Review]]'', July 4, 2003. Retrieved July 18, 2009.</ref>\n\nMalkin also opposes [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]], in which local authorities limit cooperation with national immigration agencies, such as [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE).<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/08/15/sanctuary-nation-or-sovereign-nation-its-your-choice/ \"Sanctuary Nation or Sovereign Nation: It\u2019s your choice\"], \"MichelleMalkin.com\", August 15, 2007. Retrieved December 4, 2009.</ref>\n\nShe supports coordination with federal authorities through the use of [[Immigration and Nationality Act Section 287(g)|Section 287(g)]] of the [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]] to investigate, detain, and arrest aliens on civil and criminal grounds.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2005/01/17/bushs-open-borders-nominees-2/ | title = Bush's Open Borders Nominees | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022142806/http://michellemalkin.com/2005/01/17/bushs-open-borders-nominees-2/ | archive-date=October 22, 2007 | access-date = July 18, 2009}}</ref><ref>Sanctuary Nation or Sovereign Nation: It's your choice Update: Illegal alien deportation evader Elvira Arellano will leave church sanctuary to participate in amnesty march, By Michelle Malkin, August 15, 2007, http://michellemalkin.com/2007/08/15/sanctuary-nation-or-sovereign-nation-its-your-choice/</ref> Malkin supports the detention and deportation of some immigrants, regardless of legal status, on national security grounds.<ref name=\"imdiversity2004\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Malkin gave a speech at  the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) condemning politicians, including the \"ghost\" of recently deceased Senator [[John McCain]], for failing to enact stricter immigration regulation.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Arciga | first1 = Julia | title = Michelle Malkin Goes After the 'Ghost of John McCain' at CPAC | url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/michelle-malkin-goes-after-the-ghost-of-john-mccain-at-cpac | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = The Daily Beast | date = March 1, 2019 | language = en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Michelle Malkin slams 'ghost of John McCain' on stage | url = https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/03/01/ghost-of-john-mccain-republicans-michelle-malkin-cpac-sot-vpx.cnn | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1 = Cummings | first1 = William | title = Michelle Malkin attacks the 'ghost of John McCain' in immigration talk at CPAC | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2019/03/01/michelle-malkin-blames-ghost-john-mccain-immigration-cpac/3031563002/ | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = USA TODAY | date = March 1, 2019 | language = en}}</ref>\n\n===Unemployment benefits===\nDuring an appearance as a news analyst on the roundtable segment of ABC's ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|This Week with George Stephanopoulos]]'' on August 2, 2009, she explained why she opposed another 13-week extension of [[unemployment benefits]]: \"If you put enough government cheese in front of people they are going to just keep eating it and kicking the can down the road... people will just delay getting a job until the three weeks before the benefits run out.\"<ref>{{cite video | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Video/playerIndex?id=8233167 | title = This Week with George Stephanopoulos | format = Flash | people = George Stephanopoulos, Al Hunt, Michelle Malkin, Gerald Seib, Cynthia Tucker | date = August 2, 2009 | publisher = ABC News | medium = Television production}}</ref>\n\n===Women's issues===\nIn a February 2012 column, Malkin called the \"[[War on Women]]\" a false [[narrative]], arguing rather that \"It's the [[progressivism|progressive]] [[political left|left]] in this country that has viciously and systematically slimed female conservatives for their beliefs.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aim.org/guest-column/the-war-on-conservative-women/ | title = The War on Conservative Women | author = Michelle Malkin | date = March 7, 2012 | work = [[Accuracy In Media]] | access-date = March 8, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120309101559/http://www.aim.org/guest-column/the-war-on-conservative-women/ | archive-date = March 9, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Daniel Holtzclaw ===\nMalkin took a special interest in the conviction of [[Daniel Holtzclaw]], whom she advocates as innocent.<ref>{{Citation | last = Michelle Malkin | title = CRTV: Daniel in the Den {{!}} The truth about Holtzclaw (Parts 1 and 2)|date=April 1, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmKVMklq6Wk|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> She has dedicated a significant amount of time and effort to his case, authoring multiple videos and articles on the various issues in his case.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.enidnews.com/news/local_news/documentary-about-daniel-holtzclaw-wins-honors/article_c7aadda6-5a47-56ee-a582-2cbc988ca5d5.html | title = Documentary about Daniel Holtzclaw wins honors | author = Cass Rains | work = Enid News&eagle | date = May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Legalization of cannabis===\nMalkin is a proponent of legalizing the medical use of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], dating back to 1998 when she argued in favor of the passage of [[Washington Initiative 692|Washington State's Initiative 692]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malkin |first1=Michelle |title=Hypocrisy Abounds Among Foes Of Medical Marijuana |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980922&slug=2773371 |accessdate=November 18, 2019 |work=The Seattle Times |date=September 22, 1998}}</ref> She also criticized the [[war on drugs]] as a \"dismal, costly, inefficient failure\" in a 1997 column titled \"Liberty Is Biggest Loser In Nation's War On Drugs\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malkin |first1=Michelle |title=Liberty Is Biggest Loser In Nation's War On Drugs |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970729&slug=2551904 |accessdate=November 18, 2019 |work=The Seattle Times |date=July 29, 1997}}</ref> In a 2014 interview Malkin said she was \"grateful\" for the passage of [[Colorado Amendment 64|Colorado's Amendment 64]] (legalizing recreational use), as it allowed her ailing mother-in-law to easily obtain cannabis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baca |first1=Ricardo |title=Michelle Malkin: Conservative hero and marijuana advocate (interview) |url=https://www.thecannabist.co/2014/05/16/michelle-malkin-marijuana-interview/11546/ |work=The Cannabist |date=May 16, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929162248/http://www.thecannabist.co/2014/05/16/michelle-malkin-marijuana-interview/11546/0/ |archive-date=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Support for white nationalists ===\nIn 2020, Malkin faced criticism for speaking at a conference hosted by white nationalist YouTuber [[Nick Fuentes]] and Patrick Casey, head of the neo-Nazi organization known as the [[Identity Evropa|American Identity Movement]] (formerly Identity Evropa).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> At the conference, Malkin said it was \"not anti-semitic\" to question \"whatever the precise number of people is who perished in World War II.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Malkin was dropped by the conservative [[Young America's Foundation|YAF]] organization for her support of Fuentes, who has also denied the Holocaust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/2019/11/18/young-americas-foundation-michelle-malkin-nick-fuentes/|title=Young America's Foundation Excommunicates Michelle Malkin for Defending Nick Fuentes|date=2019-11-18|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile in college at Oberlin, she began dating Jesse Malkin.<ref name=\":0\">Kelley, Debbie (September 9, 2019). [https://archive.org/download/michellemalkintheconservativepunditofelpasocountyisntgoingsilentcoloradospringsnewsgazette/Michelle%20Malkin%2C%20the%20conservative%20pundit%20of%20El%20Paso%20County%2C%20isn%27t%20going%20silent%20%7C%20Colorado%20Springs%20News%20%7C%20gazette.pdf \"Michelle Malkin, the Conservative Pundit of El Paso County, Isn't Going Silent\"]. ''[[Colorado Springs Gazette]]''. [https://archive.today/20200222220706/https://gazette.com/news/michelle-malkin-the-conservative-pundit-of-el-paso-county-isn/article_004a9dfc-d0d2-11e9-aa58-1f125a3ce51f.html Archived] from [https://gazette.com/news/michelle-malkin-the-conservative-pundit-of-el-paso-county-isn/article_004a9dfc-d0d2-11e9-aa58-1f125a3ce51f.html the original] on February 22, 2020. \"Oberlin College \u2014 where Malkin met her husband, a retired health economist who books her speaking engagements and helps run her business.\"</ref>\n\nThey married in 1993, and have two children. Jesse Malkin worked as an associate policy analyst and [[economist]] focusing on healthcare issues for the [[RAND Corporation]].<ref>Goldman, Dana P, and Malkin, Jesse D. [http://www.rand.org/commentary/2006/02/20/UPI.html \"The Health Savings Account Mirage\"], [[United Press International]], February 20, 2006.</ref> In 2004, Malkin reported on her website that her husband had left a \"lucrative health-care consulting job\" to be a [[stay-at-home dad]].<ref name=\"just\">{{cite web | first = Michelle | last = Malkin | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2005/11/19/just-a-yellow-woman-doing-a-white-mans-job/ | title = Just a yellow woman doing a white mans job | date = November 19, 2005 | website = michellemalkin.com}}</ref><ref>Michelle Malkin, [http://michellemalkin.com/2004/08/27/americas-broken-health-insurance-system/ America\u2019s broken health insurance system], August 27, 2004, [http://michellemalkin.com michellemalkin.com].</ref> Jesse Malkin helps book his wife's speaking engagements and helps her run her business.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMalkin and her family lived in [[North Bethesda, Maryland]], until 2008 when they relocated to [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref>Lloyd Grove, [http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-09-22/michelle-malkin-has-feelings-too/ Michelle Malkin Has Feelings, Too], September 22, 2009, The Daily Beast.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/opinion/outlook/article/Malkin-Correctly-remembering-terror-in-the-name-1974812.php|title=Correctly remembering terror 'in the name of Allah'|last1=Malkin|first1=Michelle|date=September 12, 2004|website=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Malkin gave a lecture at her alma mater, Oberlin College, discussing [[racism]], among other topics.<ref name=\"Beckhardt\"/> She denied allegations that she had been insensitive to the \"plight of minorities\", listing several racial epithets that had been used against her, and by relating a lesson she learned from her mother for which she is \"eternally grateful\".<ref name=\"Beckhardt\"/> When in kindergarten, Malkin went home in tears one day because her classmates had called her a racist name. But her mother comforted Michelle by telling her that everyone has [[prejudice]]s.<ref name=\"Beckhardt\">Beckhardt, Jon. [https://archive.org/download/beckhardtjon.michellemalkinalumnapunditlambastesthelefttheoberlinreviewfebruary172006/Beckhardt%2C%20Jon.%20%22Michelle%20Malkin%2C%20Alumna%20Pundit%2C%20Lambastes%20the%20Left%22%2C%20The%20Oberlin%20Review%2C%20February%2017%2C%202006.pdf \"Michelle Malkin, Alumna Pundit, Lambastes the Left\"]. [[The Oberlin Review]], February 17, 2006. [https://archive.today/20200222202025/http://www2.oberlin.edu/stupub/ocreview/2006/02/17/news/article4.html Archived] from [http://www.oberlin.edu/stupub/ocreview/2006/02/17/news/article4.html the original].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Conservatism}}\n{{Commons category|Michelle Malkin}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official website|http://www.michellemalkin.com}}\n*[https://twitter.com/michellemalkin Michelle Malkin] on [[Twitter]]\n* [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.html Michelle Malkin Features] at [[Creators Syndicate]]\n* [http://www.townhall.com/columnists/michellemalkin/archive.shtml Archive] of Malkin's columns at [[Townhall.com]]\n* [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2009/feb/19/columnist-isnt-smiling-over-swastika-in-rally/ \"Columnist isn't smiling over swastika in rally photo\"]. ''Rocky Mountain News''. February 19, 2009.\n* [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin112404.asp \"Michelle Malkin: Grace, gratitude, and G-d\"]. ''Jewish World Review''. November 24, 2004.\n* [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin.archives.asp Archive of Malkin's columns] at ''[[Jewish World Review]]''\n* {{C-SPAN|michellemalkin}}\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20140328060105/http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/173558-1/Michelle+Malkin.aspx ''Booknotes'' interview with Malkin on ''Invasion'', December 8, 2002.]\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Malk ''In Depth'' interview with Malkin, January 3, 2010]\n\n{{Michelle Malkin}}\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malkin, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:Competitive Enterprise Institute]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Holy Spirit High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania political journalists]]\n[[Category:Oberlin College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Absecon, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Republicans]]\n[[Category:Maryland Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:Critics of Marxism]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Opposition to Islam in the United States]]\n[[Category:American women television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author and  journalist}}\n{{Distinguish|Michele Merkin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2018}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Michelle Malkin\n| image              = Michelle Malkin 2008 2.jpg\n| birth_name         = Michelle Maglalang\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1970|10|20}}<ref name=\"nahm\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Oberlin College]]\n| occupation         = Author, [[Print syndication|syndicated]] [[columnist]], [[television personality]], and [[blog]]ger, [[Fox News]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Jesse Malkin|1993}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|michellemalkin.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Michelle Malkin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|l|k|\u026a|n}}; n\u00e9e '''Maglalang'''; born October 20, 1970) is an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] blogger, political commentator, author and businesswoman. Her weekly [[Print syndication|syndicated]] [[column (newspaper)|column]] appears in a number of newspapers and websites.<ref name=\"pitts\">[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2008-03-09/news/0803080095_1_michelle-malkin-moonbats-daughter \"Right at home\" Pitts, Jonathan.] ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''<span>, March 9, 2008, page E 1.</span></ref> She was a [[Fox News]] contributor and has been a guest on [[MSNBC]], [[C-SPAN]], and national radio programs. Malkin has written four books published by [[Regnery Publishing]]. She founded the conservative websites [[Twitchy]] and ''[[Hot Air]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/12/michelle-malkin-laughs-liberal-tweets-all-way-bank/355984/ | title = Michelle Malkin Laughs at Liberal Tweets All the Way to the Bank | last = Bump | first = Philip | date = December 10, 2013 | work = The Atlantic|access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Amanda Carpenter]] has reported that Malkin began to \"link arms with the most vocal elements of the white nationalist movement\" in 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://thebulwark.com/michelle-malkin-mother-of-groypers/|title=Michelle Malkin: Mother of Groypers|date=2020-03-09|website=The Bulwark|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Malkin faced criticism for her association with white nationalists and neo-Nazis, including [[Nick Fuentes]] and [[Identity Evropa]]. In February 2020, she was dropped by conservative organization [[Young America's Foundation]] (YAF) due to her support of Holocaust deniers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/American-Politics/Michelle-Malkin-shunned-by-conservatives-over-support-for-antisemites-608349|title=Michelle Malkin shunned by conservatives over support for antisemites|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/politics/conservatives-blast-michelle-malkins-anti-semitic-questions-once-admired-her-this-is-disgusting/|title=Conservatives Blast Michelle Malkin on 'Anti-Semitic' Questions|date=2020-03-03|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMichelle Malkin was born October 20, 1970<ref name=\"nahm\" /> in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], to [[Philippine nationality law|Philippine citizens]] Rafaela (n\u00e9e Perez) \u2013 a homemaker and teacher \u2013 and Apolo DeCastro Maglalang, who was then a physician-in-training.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Several months prior to Malkin's birth, her parents had immigrated to the United States on an employer-sponsored visa.<ref name=\"lamb\">{{cite web | author = Lamb, Brian | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071013191746/http://booknotes.org/Transcript/?ProgramID=1705 | archivedate = October 13, 2007|url-status=dead | title = Booknotes Transcript on \"Invasion: How America Still Welcomes Terrorists\" | work = [[Booknotes]] | publisher = C-SPAN | url = http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/173558-1/Michelle+Malkin.aspx}}</ref> After her father finished his medical training, the family moved<ref>{{cite web | title = In Depth | publisher = Book TV | date = January 3, 2011 | url = http://www.c-span.org/video/?291010-1/depth-michelle-malkin}}</ref> to [[Absecon, New Jersey]]. Malkin has a younger brother.<ref name=\"MM\">{{cite web | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2004/12/03/maglalangadingdoing-this/ | title = Maglalangadingdong this | publisher = MichelleMalkin.com | author = Malkin, Michelle | date = December 3, 2004 | accessdate = May 24, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She has described her parents as [[Ronald Reagan]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] who were \"not incredibly politically active\".<ref name=\"nahm\">Nahm, H Y. [http://www.goldsea.com/Personalities/Malkin/malkin.html \"Michelle Malkin: The Radical Right's Asian Pitbull\"], \"Goldsea Asian American\". Retrieved July 16, 2009.</ref>\n\nMalkin, a [[Roman Catholic]],<ref name=\"nahm\"/><ref>Malkin, Michelle, (April 9, 2010), [http://michellemalkin.com/2010/04/09/the-pfleger-ization-of-the-catholic-church/ \"The Pfleger-ization of the Catholic Church\"], MichelleMalkin.com, April 9, 2010. Retrieved August 17, 2011.</ref> attended [[Holy Spirit High School (New Jersey)|Holy Spirit Roman Catholic High School]], where she edited the school newspaper and aspired to become a concert [[pianist]].<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Following her graduation in 1988, she enrolled at [[Oberlin College]].<ref name=\"nahm\"/> Malkin had planned to pursue a [[bachelor's degree]] in music, but changed her major to English.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> During her college years, she worked as a press inserter, tax preparation aide, and network news librarian.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/personalities/michelle-malkin/bio/#s=m-q | title = On Air Personalities: Michelle Malkin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110818050151/http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/personalities/michelle-malkin/bio/#s=m-q |archive-date=August 18, 2011 | work = Fox News | access-date = August 18, 2011}}</ref> Her first article for the paper heavily criticized Oberlin's [[affirmative action]] program and received a \"hugely negative response\" from other students on campus.<ref name=\"nahm\"/> She graduated in 1992<ref name=\"bookshelf\">[http://www.oberlin.edu/alummag/spring2003/bookshelf.html Bookshelf: Invasion By Michelle Malkin], Reviewed by Jan Ting, ''Oberlin Alumni Magazine'', Spring 2003. Retrieved August 18, 2011.</ref> and later described her ''alma mater'' as \"radically left-wing\".<ref name=\"goliath\">Article preview. [https://web.archive.org/web/20080319092906/http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0199-5264457_ITM \"Michelle Malkin\"], ''[[The American Enterprise]]'', September 1, 2005. Retrieved on March 4, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Journalism===\n[[File:Michelle Malkin by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Malkin speaking in South Carolina in 2016]]\nMalkin began her journalism career at the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'', working as a columnist from 1992 to 1994. In 1995, she worked in [[Washington, D.C.]] as a journalism fellow at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.foxnews.com/bios/talent/michelle-malkin/ | title = Michelle Malkin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090819151619/http://www.foxnews.com/bios/talent/michelle-malkin | archive-date=August 19, 2009 | work = FoxNews.com | access-date = July 23, 2009}}</ref> a free-market, anti-government regulation, [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] [[think tank]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/05/AR2009030503293.html | title = Europe Advises U.S. Officials on Climate | first1 = Juliet | last1 = Eilperin | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] | date = March 6, 2009}}</ref> In 1996, she moved to [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], where she wrote columns for ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. Malkin became a nationally [[print syndication|syndicated]] columnist with [[Creators Syndicate]] in 1999.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.html \"Michelle Malkin's Latest Opinion Column HLML\"], [[Creators Syndicate]]</ref><ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.rss \"Michelle Malkin's Latest Opinion Column RSS\"], [[Creators Syndicate]].</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2006, ''[[Hot Air]]'', a \"conservative Internet broadcast network\", went into operation, with Malkin as founder/CEO.<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/4/prweb376471.htm \"Conservative Internet Broadcast Network Debuts\"], [[PR Web]], April 24, 2006, Accessed July 18, 2009</ref> The site's staff at launch included [[Allahpundit]] and Bryan Preston. Preston was replaced by [[Ed Morrissey]] on February 25, 2008.<ref>Morrissey, Ed.[http://www.captainsquartersblog.com/mt/archives/017106.php \"The Road Goes Ever On\"] February 25, 2008</ref> In February 2010, Hotair.com was bought by [[Salem Communications]] and is no longer administered by Malkin.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2010/02/21/a-note-on-the-acquisition-of-hot-air/ \"A note on the acquisition of Hot Air\"] February 21, 2010</ref>\n\nFor years, Malkin was a frequent commentator for [[Fox News]] and a regular guest host of ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]''. In 2007, she announced that she would not return to ''The O'Reilly Factor'', claiming that Fox News had mishandled a dispute over derogatory statements made about her by [[Geraldo Rivera]] in a ''[[The Boston Globe|Boston Globe]]'' interview.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/09/01/geraldo-rivera-unhinged \"Geraldo Rivera unhinged\"], MichelleMalkin.com, September 1, 2007.</ref> Since 2007, she has concentrated on her writing, blogging, and public speaking, although she still appears on television occasionally, especially with [[Sean Hannity#Television|Sean Hannity]] and formerly with [[Greta Van Susteren]] on Fox News and ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' once a week.\n\nMalkin had been a contributor to [[Conservative Review|CRTV]], but left the network following its merger with [[TheBlaze]] in December 2018 and joined competitor [[Newsmax TV]].<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Swanson | first1 = Ian | title = Michelle Malkin departs CRTV one day after Blaze merger announced | url = https://thehill.com/homenews/media/419677-michelle-malkin-departs-crtv-one-day-after-blaze-merger-announced | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = TheHill | date = December 4, 2018 | language = en}}</ref>\n\nMalkin also founded the website [[Twitchy]], a [[Twitter]] [[content curation]] site.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://twitchy.com/about/ | title = About Us | work = Twitchy | access-date = September 4, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130806095639/http://twitchy.com/about/ | archive-date = August 6, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nA day after the death of journalist [[Cokie Roberts]], Malkin claimed that Cokie was \"One of the first Guilty Culprits of Fake News\" <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/michelle-malkin-smears-cokie-roberts-on-the-day-of-her-death-one-of-the-first-guilty-culprits-of-fake-news | title = Michelle Malkin Smears Cokie Roberts on the Day of Her Death: 'One of the First Guilty Culprits of Fake News' | last = Baragona | first = Justin | date = September 18, 2019|access-date=September 19, 2019 | language = en}}</ref>.  [[Brian Stelter]] quickly said, during the panel discussion, \"You're attacking her today.  I just want to be clear: the body isn't even cold yet.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Books===\nMalkin has written a total of seven books.\n\nHer first book, ''[[Invasion: How America Still Welcomes Terrorists, Criminals, and Other Foreign Menaces]]'' (2002)<ref>[[Regnery Publishing]], 2002, {{ISBN|0-89526-075-1}}</ref> was a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestseller]].\n\nIn 2004, she wrote ''[[In Defense of Internment|In Defense of Internment: The Case for 'Racial Profiling' in World War II and the War on Terror]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Malkin|first=Michelle|title=In Defense of Internment: The Case for 'Racial Profiling' in World War II and the War on Terror|url=https://archive.org/details/indefen_mal_2004_00_5055|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=Regnery Publishing|isbn=978-0-89526-051-2}}</ref> defending the U.S. government's [[Japanese American internment|internment]] of 112,000 Japanese Americans in prison camps during [[World War II]], and arguing that the same procedures could be used on [[Arab people|Arab]]- and [[Muslim]]-Americans today. The book engendered harsh criticism from several [[Asian American]] civil rights organizations.<ref name=\"imdiversity2004\">{{Cite press release | publisher = Japanese American citizens League | url = http://www.imdiversity.com/Villages/asian/politics_law/archives/jacl_malkin_response_0804.asp | title = JACL Responds to \"Defense of Internment, Case for Race Profiling\" | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081007095519/http://www.imdiversity.com/villages/asian/politics_law/archives/jacl_malkin_response_0804.asp | archive-date=October 7, 2008 | website = IMdiversity.com | date = August 24, 2004 | access-date = July 18, 2009}}</ref> The Historians' Committee for Fairness, an organization of scholars and professional researchers, condemned the book for not having undergone [[peer review]] and argued that its central thesis is false.<ref>Historians' Committee for Fairness. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070805083832/http://hnn.us/readcomment.php?id=40982 \"Open Letter to Michelle Malkin\"] [[History News Network]], August 31, 2004. (archived from [http://hnn.us/readcomment.php?id=40982 the original] on August 5, 2007).</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = In disgrace or in defense? | first = Douglas | last = Brown | work = Denver Post. | date = September 2, 2004 | page = F.01}}</ref> As a result of the controversy, the Hawaii-based newspaper ''[[MidWeek]]'' dropped her column in August 2004;<ref>{{cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2004/08/27/book-buzz-2/ | title = Book Buzz | publisher = michellemalkin.com | date = August 27, 2004}}</ref> ''[[The Virginian-Pilot]]'' called her \"an Asian [[Ann Coulter]]\" and dropped her column in November 2004.<ref>Editor & Publisher Staff.[https://web.archive.org/web/20050312041405/http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000724900 \"Virginia Paper Drops Columnist Malkin\"], ''[[Editor and Publisher]]'', November 22, 2004. Retrieved July 18, 2009.</ref> Malkin responded: \"I'm not Asian, I'm American\", and described the comparison to Coulter as \"a compliment\".<ref>{{Cite web | last1 = Malzberg | first1 = Steve | url = http://www.newsmax.com/archives/ic/2004/11/28/124846.shtml | title = Malkin - Liberal Bigotry on the Rise | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20050406145048/http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2004/11/28/124846.shtml | archive-date=April 6, 2005 | work = [[NewsMax Media|NewsMax.com]] | date = November 28, 2004}}</ref>\n\nMalkin's third book, ''Unhinged: Exposing Liberals Gone Wild'', was released in October 2005.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Unhinged: Exposing Liberals Gone Wild | publisher = Regnery Publishing | date = 2005 | isbn = 0-89526-030-1 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/unhingedexposing00malk }}</ref>\n\n''[[Culture of Corruption: Obama and His Team of Tax Cheats, Crooks, and Cronies]]'', Malkin's fourth book, was released in July 2009<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Regnery Publishing | date = 2009 | isbn = 978-1-59698-109-6 | title = Culture of Corruption: Obama and His Team of Tax Cheats, Crooks, and Cronies}}</ref> and was a ''The New York Times'' Non-Fiction, Hardcover Best Seller for six weeks.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Sept. 20, 2009 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/20/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html?_r=1&ref=bestseller | access-date = October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"malkin080509\">Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2009/08/05/culture-of-corruption-hits-1-thank-you/ \"Lead Story: Culture of Corruption hits #1: Thank you!\"], michellemalkin.com, August 5, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Dixler | first = Elsa | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/16/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html | title = August 16, 2009 Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = August 16, 2009 | access-date = May 8, 2012}}</ref> Malkin said she hoped the book would \"shatter completely the myths of hope and change in the new politics in Washington\", described the Obama administration as run by \"influence peddlers, power brokers and very wealthy people\", and called it \"one of the most corrupt administrations in recent memory\".<ref name=\"hannityshow\">Malkin, Michelle.[http://www.foxnews.com/video2/video08.html?maven_referralObject=7441258&maven_referralPlaylistId=&sRevUrl=http://www.foxnews.com/hannity/index.html \"Interview on the Sean Hannity Show\"],\"Fox News Channel\", FoxNews.com, July 27, 2009. Retrieved July 29, 2009.</ref> She later discussed chapter two of the book, \"Bitter Half: First Crony Michelle Obama\", on [[Today (NBC program)|NBC's ''Today'' show]]. She described [[Michelle Obama]] as \"steeped in the politics of the [[Daley family|Daley machine]]\", and as having based her professional career on nepotism and \"old white boy\" network connections.<ref>{{cite video | url = http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26184891/vp/32200089#32200089 | title = Today show | format = Flash | people = Matt Lauer, Michelle Malkin | date = July 29, 2009 | publisher = NBC News | medium = Television production | accessdate = July 29, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n''Who Built That: Awe-Inspiring Stories of American Tinkerpreneurs'', released May 2015,<ref>{{cite book | author = Michelle Malkin | title = Who Built That: Awe-Inspiring Stories of American Tinkerpreneurs | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zA9DCQAAQBAJ | date = May 19, 2015 | publisher = Simon and Schuster | isbn = 978-1-4767-8494-6}}</ref> presents stories of American inventors and business people, directly challenging the \"[[you didn't build that]]\" statement made by President [[Barack Obama]] on July 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | last = Bedard | first = Paul | title = Michelle Malkin's 'Who Built That' storms onto bestseller list | url = http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-malkins-who-built-that-storms-onto-bestseller-list/article/2565114 | newspaper = Washington Examiner | date = May 27, 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}<br />{{cite news | last = Lozado | first = Carlos | title = Michelle Malkin's new book has a chapter in which she pretends to be a roll of toilet paper | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/book-party/wp/2015/06/03/michelle-malkins-new-book-has-a-chapter-in-which-she-pretends-to-be-a-roll-of-toilet-paper/ | newspaper = Washington post | date = June 3, 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Sold Out (book)|''Sold Out: How High-Tech Billionaires & Bipartisan Beltway Crapweasels Are Screwing America's Best & Brightest Workers'']], M. Malkin and J. Miano, [[Simon & Schuster]] Audio/Mercury Ink (November 10, 2015)\n\n''Open Borders Inc.: Who's Funding America's Destruction?'' Michelle Malkin, [[Regnery Publishing]] (September 10, 2019)\n\n==Blogging==\n\nIn June 2004, Malkin launched a political blog, MichelleMalkin.com.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2004/06/08/extreme-makeover/ \"Extreme Makeover\"], \"MichelleMalkin.com\", June 8, 2004.</ref> A 2007 memo from the [[National Republican Senatorial Committee]] described Malkin as one of the five \"best-read national conservative bloggers\",<ref>Budoff, Carrie. [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0607/4483.html \"GOP issues rules to avoid Macaca moments\"], ''[[The Politico]]'', June 13, 2007</ref> and as of 2012 [[Technorati]] had ranked MichelleMalkin.com in its \"Top 100 blogs of all types\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://technorati.com/search?q=michelle&return=sites | title = Blogs relating to \"michelle\" (4 blogs found out of 1187182) | publisher = Technorati.com | date =  | accessdate = May 8, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2011, the people search company [[PeekYou]] claimed that Malkin had the largest digital footprint of any political blogger.<ref>{{cite web | author = PeekYou Team | url = http://score.peekyou.com/the-peekscores-of-30-top-political-bloggers/ | title = The PeekScores of 30 Top Political Bloggers | publisher = score.peekyou.com | date = November 30, 2011 | accessdate = May 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528124319/http://score.peekyou.com/the-peekscores-of-30-top-political-bloggers/ |archive-date=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMalkin accused hip hop artist [[Akon]] of degrading women in a ''HotAir'' YouTube video in May 2007. Following this, Akon's record label, [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG), issued a [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act|DMCA]] takedown notice removing the video.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://www.michellemalkin.com/archives/007446.htm | title = Akon's record company abuses DMCA to stifle criticism on YouTube | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070505053513/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007446.htm | archive-date=May 5, 2007 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = May 3, 2007}}</ref> UMG retracted the notice after the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] joined Malkin in contesting the removal as a misuse of copyright law.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007514.htm | title = UMG & YouTube retreat over Akon report | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = May 14, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070516041140/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/007514.htm | archive-date=May 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Universal Music Group Backs Off Claims to Michelle Malkin Video | url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2007/05/universal-music-group-backs-claims-michelle-malkin-video | website = Electronic Frontier Foundation | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | language = en | date = May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nMichelleMalkin.com was revamped and moved to a larger server on [[WordPress]] in  June 2007.<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/06/19/welcome-to-the-new-michellemalkincom \"Welcome to the new michellemalkin.com!\"],\"MichelleMalkin.com\", June 19, 2007.</ref> \n\nMalkin has also been a contributor to anti-immigration website [[VDARE]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-08-14/alt-right-charlottesville-daily-stormer-racism-white-supremacists | title = Op-Ed: White supremacist publications took a hit after Charlottesville. Now they're stronger than ever | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jamil Hussein===\n{{Main|Jamil Hussein controversy}}\nMalkin was among the first of several bloggers who questioned the credibility and even the existence of Iraqi police Captain \"Jamil Hussein\" who had been used as a source by the [[Associated Press]] in over 60 stories about the Iraq war. The controversy started in November 2006 when the AP reported that six Iraqis had been burned alive as they left a mosque and that four mosques had been destroyed, citing Hussein as one of its sources. In January 2007, Malkin visited Baghdad, and stated, \"the Iraqi Ministry of Interior says disputed Associated Press source Jamil Hussein does exist. At least one story he told the AP just doesn't check out: The Sunni mosques that as Hussein claimed and AP reported as 'destroyed,' 'torched' and 'burned and blown up' are all still standing. So the credibility of every AP story relying on Jamil Hussein remains dubious.\"<ref name=malkin20070121>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/01/21/fact-checking-the-ap-and-jamil-hussein/ \"Fact-checking the AP and Jamil Hussein\"], MichelleMalkin.com, January 21, 2007.</ref> Malkin has since issued a correction for her denial of Hussein's existence, \"I relayed information from multiple sources\u2014CPATT, Centcom, and two other military sources on the ground in Iraq\u2014that the Associated Press's disputed source, Jamil Hussein, could not be found.\" [...] \"I regret the error,\" but still contested AP claims of destroyed mosques and civilians burned alive.<ref name=malkin20070121 /><ref name=MM6641>{{cite web | author = Malkin, Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/006641.htm | title = Corrections | date = March 4, 2016 | quote = I relayed information from multiple sources--CPATT, Centcom, and two other military sources on the ground in Iraq-- that the Associated Press's disputed source, Jamil Hussein, could not be found. As I noted on the 4th, the AP reported that the Ministry of Interior in Iraq has now said a Captain Jamil Hussein does work in the al Khadra police station. I regret the error. But no blogger should apologize for raising legitimate questions about AP's transparency, its reliance on local foreign stringers of dubious origins, and information that sources such as Hussein have provided the AP. I will continue to pursue some of the unresolved issues related to this. |url-status=unfit | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070217113609/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/006641.htm | archivedate = February 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Students Against War controversy===\nIn April 2006, Students Against War (SAW), a campus group at [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], staged a protest against the presence of military recruiters on campus, and sent out a [[press release]] containing contact details (names, phone numbers and e-mail addresses) of three student leaders for use by reporters. Malkin included these contact details in a blog column entitled \"Seditious Santa Cruz vs. America\".<ref name=MM04974>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004974.htm | title = Seditious Santa Cruz vs. America | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419062349/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004974.htm | archive-date=April 19, 2006 | website = michellemalkin.com | date = April 12, 2006}}</ref> Malkin claimed the contact information was originally taken from SAW's own website, but that later SAW had removed it and had \"wiped\" the \"cached version\".<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004999.htm | title = More Thuggery In Santa Cruz | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080720033805/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/004999.htm | archive-date=July 20, 2008 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = April 17, 2006}}</ref> The students asked Malkin to remove the contact details from her blog, but Malkin reposted them several times<ref name=\"sentinel\">{{Cite web | author = Sentinel | url = http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2006/04/22/18170531.php | title = Malkin moves, takes child from school, as SC students retaliate | work = Santa Cruz Indymedia | date = April 22, 2006 | access-date = July 20, 2009}}</ref> writing in her blog: \"I am leaving it up. If you are contacting them, I do not condone death threats or foul language. As for SAW, my message is this: You are responsible for your individual actions. Other individuals are responsible for theirs. Grow up and take responsibility.\"<ref name=MM04974/>\n\nSAW remarked: \"Due to the continued irresponsible actions of some bloggers, members of the group have received numerous death threats and anti-Semitic comments through phone calls and emails.\"<ref name=\"students\">\nStudents Against The War. [http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2006/04/19/18164431.php \"Far-Right Threats Fail to Distract from Santa Cruz Protest Successes\"], April 19, 2006,</ref> A blog war ensued. Malkin claimed that she received hostile e-mails,<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/archives/005008.htm | title = The Moonbats Strike Back | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060503030350/http://michellemalkin.com/archives/005008.htm | archive-date=May 3, 2006 | website = MichelleMalkin.com | date = April 17, 2006}}</ref> then her private home address, phone number, photos of her neighborhood and maps to her house were published on several websites. The ''[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]'' reported receiving an email from Malkin saying that this forced her to remove one of her children from school and move her family.<ref>{{cite web | author = Sideman, Roger | url = http://www.scsextra.com/story.php?sid=37840 | title = Cyber war over UCSC protest heats up | work = [[Santa Cruz Sentinel]] | date = April 22, 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120306162152/http://www.scsextra.com/story.php?sid=37840 | archivedate = March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnother controversy involving private addresses began on July 1, 2006, when Malkin and other bloggers commented on a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' Travel section article that had featured the town where Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] and Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] owned summer homes. The article included a picture of Rumsfeld's long tree-lined driveway that showed a birdhouse and small portion of the housefront.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Kilborn | first = Peter T. | url = http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/06/30/travel/escapes/30michaels.html?ex=1309320000&en=538a0c0e85134892&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | title = Weekends with the President's Men | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070906114610/http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/06/30/travel/escapes/30michaels.html?ex=1309320000&en=538a0c0e85134892&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | archive-date=September 6, 2007 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = June 30, 2006}}</ref> Malkin declared that this story was part of \"a concerted, organized effort to dig up and publicize the private home information of prominent conservatives in the media and blogosphere to intimidate them.\" The photos of Rumsfeld's house were taken with Rumsfeld's permission.<ref>{{cite web | last = Greenwald | first = Glenn | url = http://glenngreenwald.blogspot.com/2006/07/what-is-left-of-malkin-hinderaker-and.html | title = What is left of Malkin, Hinderaker and Horowitz's credibility? | publisher = Unclaimed Territory | date = July 3, 2006 | accessdate = May 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\n===Immigration===\nMalkin opposes [[birthright citizenship in the United States|birthright citizenship]] to U.S.-born children of foreign tourists, temporary foreign workers, and [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]]. She claims this undermines the integrity of citizenship and national security, and argues that the [[Citizenship Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment to the Constitution]], \"originally intended to ensure the citizenship rights of newly freed slaves and their families after the Civil War, has evolved into a magnet for alien lawbreakers and a shield for terrorist infiltrators and enemy combatants\".<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin070403.asp \"What makes an American?\"], ''[[Jewish World Review]]'', July 4, 2003. Retrieved July 18, 2009.</ref>\n\nMalkin also opposes [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]], in which local authorities limit cooperation with national immigration agencies, such as [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE).<ref>Malkin, Michelle. [http://michellemalkin.com/2007/08/15/sanctuary-nation-or-sovereign-nation-its-your-choice/ \"Sanctuary Nation or Sovereign Nation: It\u2019s your choice\"], \"MichelleMalkin.com\", August 15, 2007. Retrieved December 4, 2009.</ref>\n\nShe supports coordination with federal authorities through the use of [[Immigration and Nationality Act Section 287(g)|Section 287(g)]] of the [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]] to investigate, detain, and arrest aliens on civil and criminal grounds.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Malkin | first = Michelle | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2005/01/17/bushs-open-borders-nominees-2/ | title = Bush's Open Borders Nominees | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022142806/http://michellemalkin.com/2005/01/17/bushs-open-borders-nominees-2/ | archive-date=October 22, 2007 | access-date = July 18, 2009}}</ref><ref>Sanctuary Nation or Sovereign Nation: It's your choice Update: Illegal alien deportation evader Elvira Arellano will leave church sanctuary to participate in amnesty march, By Michelle Malkin, August 15, 2007, http://michellemalkin.com/2007/08/15/sanctuary-nation-or-sovereign-nation-its-your-choice/</ref> Malkin supports the detention and deportation of some immigrants, regardless of legal status, on national security grounds.<ref name=\"imdiversity2004\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Malkin gave a speech at  the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) condemning politicians, including the \"ghost\" of recently deceased Senator [[John McCain]], for failing to enact stricter immigration regulation.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Arciga | first1 = Julia | title = Michelle Malkin Goes After the 'Ghost of John McCain' at CPAC | url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/michelle-malkin-goes-after-the-ghost-of-john-mccain-at-cpac | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = The Daily Beast | date = March 1, 2019 | language = en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Michelle Malkin slams 'ghost of John McCain' on stage | url = https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/03/01/ghost-of-john-mccain-republicans-michelle-malkin-cpac-sot-vpx.cnn | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1 = Cummings | first1 = William | title = Michelle Malkin attacks the 'ghost of John McCain' in immigration talk at CPAC | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2019/03/01/michelle-malkin-blames-ghost-john-mccain-immigration-cpac/3031563002/ | accessdate = April 22, 2019 | work = USA TODAY | date = March 1, 2019 | language = en}}</ref>\n\n===Unemployment benefits===\nDuring an appearance as a news analyst on the roundtable segment of ABC's ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|This Week with George Stephanopoulos]]'' on August 2, 2009, she explained why she opposed another 13-week extension of [[unemployment benefits]]: \"If you put enough government cheese in front of people they are going to just keep eating it and kicking the can down the road... people will just delay getting a job until the three weeks before the benefits run out.\"<ref>{{cite video | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Video/playerIndex?id=8233167 | title = This Week with George Stephanopoulos | format = Flash | people = George Stephanopoulos, Al Hunt, Michelle Malkin, Gerald Seib, Cynthia Tucker | date = August 2, 2009 | publisher = ABC News | medium = Television production}}</ref>\n\n===Women's issues===\nIn a February 2012 column, Malkin called the \"[[War on Women]]\" a false [[narrative]], arguing rather that \"It's the [[progressivism|progressive]] [[political left|left]] in this country that has viciously and systematically slimed female conservatives for their beliefs.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aim.org/guest-column/the-war-on-conservative-women/ | title = The War on Conservative Women | author = Michelle Malkin | date = March 7, 2012 | work = [[Accuracy In Media]] | access-date = March 8, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120309101559/http://www.aim.org/guest-column/the-war-on-conservative-women/ | archive-date = March 9, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Daniel Holtzclaw ===\nMalkin took a special interest in the conviction of [[Daniel Holtzclaw]], whom she advocates as innocent.<ref>{{Citation | last = Michelle Malkin | title = CRTV: Daniel in the Den {{!}} The truth about Holtzclaw (Parts 1 and 2)|date=April 1, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmKVMklq6Wk|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> She has dedicated a significant amount of time and effort to his case, authoring multiple videos and articles on the various issues in his case.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.enidnews.com/news/local_news/documentary-about-daniel-holtzclaw-wins-honors/article_c7aadda6-5a47-56ee-a582-2cbc988ca5d5.html | title = Documentary about Daniel Holtzclaw wins honors | author = Cass Rains | work = Enid News&eagle | date = May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Legalization of cannabis===\nMalkin is a proponent of legalizing the medical use of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], dating back to 1998 when she argued in favor of the passage of [[Washington Initiative 692|Washington State's Initiative 692]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malkin |first1=Michelle |title=Hypocrisy Abounds Among Foes Of Medical Marijuana |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980922&slug=2773371 |accessdate=November 18, 2019 |work=The Seattle Times |date=September 22, 1998}}</ref> She also criticized the [[war on drugs]] as a \"dismal, costly, inefficient failure\" in a 1997 column titled \"Liberty Is Biggest Loser In Nation's War On Drugs\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malkin |first1=Michelle |title=Liberty Is Biggest Loser In Nation's War On Drugs |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970729&slug=2551904 |accessdate=November 18, 2019 |work=The Seattle Times |date=July 29, 1997}}</ref> In a 2014 interview Malkin said she was \"grateful\" for the passage of [[Colorado Amendment 64|Colorado's Amendment 64]] (legalizing recreational use), as it allowed her ailing mother-in-law to easily obtain cannabis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baca |first1=Ricardo |title=Michelle Malkin: Conservative hero and marijuana advocate (interview) |url=https://www.thecannabist.co/2014/05/16/michelle-malkin-marijuana-interview/11546/ |work=The Cannabist |date=May 16, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929162248/http://www.thecannabist.co/2014/05/16/michelle-malkin-marijuana-interview/11546/0/ |archive-date=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Support for white nationalists ===\nIn 2020, Malkin faced criticism for speaking at a conference hosted by white nationalist YouTuber [[Nick Fuentes]] and Patrick Casey, head of the neo-Nazi organization known as the [[Identity Evropa|American Identity Movement]] (formerly Identity Evropa).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> At the conference, Malkin said it was \"not anti-semitic\" to question \"whatever the precise number of people is who perished in World War II.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Malkin was dropped by the conservative [[Young America's Foundation|YAF]] organization for her support of Fuentes, who has also denied the Holocaust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/2019/11/18/young-americas-foundation-michelle-malkin-nick-fuentes/|title=Young America's Foundation Excommunicates Michelle Malkin for Defending Nick Fuentes|date=2019-11-18|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile in college at Oberlin, she began dating Jesse Malkin.<ref name=\":0\">Kelley, Debbie (September 9, 2019). [https://archive.org/download/michellemalkintheconservativepunditofelpasocountyisntgoingsilentcoloradospringsnewsgazette/Michelle%20Malkin%2C%20the%20conservative%20pundit%20of%20El%20Paso%20County%2C%20isn%27t%20going%20silent%20%7C%20Colorado%20Springs%20News%20%7C%20gazette.pdf \"Michelle Malkin, the Conservative Pundit of El Paso County, Isn't Going Silent\"]. ''[[Colorado Springs Gazette]]''. [https://archive.today/20200222220706/https://gazette.com/news/michelle-malkin-the-conservative-pundit-of-el-paso-county-isn/article_004a9dfc-d0d2-11e9-aa58-1f125a3ce51f.html Archived]from [https://gazette.com/news/michelle-malkin-the-conservative-pundit-of-el-paso-county-isn/article_004a9dfc-d0d2-11e9-aa58-1f125a3ce51f.html the original] on February 22, 2020. \"Oberlin College \u2014 where Malkin met her husband, a retired health economist who books her speaking engagements and helps run her business.\"</ref>\n\nThey married in 1993, and have two children. Jesse Malkin worked as an associate policy analyst and [[economist]] focusing on healthcare issues for the [[RAND Corporation]].<ref>Goldman, Dana P, and Malkin, Jesse D. [http://www.rand.org/commentary/2006/02/20/UPI.html \"The Health Savings Account Mirage\"], [[United Press International]], February 20, 2006.</ref> In 2004, Malkin reported on her website that her husband had left a \"lucrative health-care consulting job\" to be a [[stay-at-home dad]].<ref name=\"just\">{{cite web | first = Michelle | last = Malkin | url = http://michellemalkin.com/2005/11/19/just-a-yellow-woman-doing-a-white-mans-job/ | title = Just a yellow woman doing a white mans job | date = November 19, 2005 | website = michellemalkin.com}}</ref><ref>Michelle Malkin, [http://michellemalkin.com/2004/08/27/americas-broken-health-insurance-system/ America\u2019s broken health insurance system], August 27, 2004, [http://michellemalkin.com michellemalkin.com].</ref> Jesse Malkin helps book his wifes speaking engagements and helps her run her business.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMalkin and her family lived in [[North Bethesda, Maryland]], until 2008 when they relocated to [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref>Lloyd Grove, [http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2009-09-22/michelle-malkin-has-feelings-too/ Michelle Malkin Has Feelings, Too], September 22, 2009, The Daily Beast.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/opinion/outlook/article/Malkin-Correctly-remembering-terror-in-the-name-1974812.php|title=Correctly remembering terror 'in the name of Allah'|last1=Malkin|first1=Michelle|date=September 12, 2004|website=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Malkin gave a lecture at her alma mater, Oberlin College, discussing [[racism]], among other topics.<ref name=\"Beckhardt\"/> She denied allegations that she had been insensitive to the \"plight of minorities\", listing several racial epithets that had been used against her, and by relating a lesson she learned from her mother for which she is \"eternally grateful\".<ref name=\"Beckhardt\"/> When in kindergarten, Malkin went home in tears one day because her classmates had called her a racist name. But her mother comforted Michelle by telling her that everyone has [[prejudice]]s.<ref name=\"Beckhardt\">Beckhardt, Jon. [https://archive.org/download/beckhardtjon.michellemalkinalumnapunditlambastesthelefttheoberlinreviewfebruary172006/Beckhardt%2C%20Jon.%20%22Michelle%20Malkin%2C%20Alumna%20Pundit%2C%20Lambastes%20the%20Left%22%2C%20The%20Oberlin%20Review%2C%20February%2017%2C%202006.pdf \"Michelle Malkin, Alumna Pundit, Lambastes the Left\"]. [[The Oberlin Review]], February 17, 2006. [https://archive.today/20200222202025/http://www2.oberlin.edu/stupub/ocreview/2006/02/17/news/article4.html Archived] from [http://www.oberlin.edu/stupub/ocreview/2006/02/17/news/article4.html the original].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Conservatism}}\n{{Commons category|Michelle Malkin}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official website|http://www.michellemalkin.com}}\n*[https://twitter.com/michellemalkin Michelle Malkin] on [[Twitter]]\n* [http://www.creators.com/opinion/michelle-malkin.html Michelle Malkin Features] at [[Creators Syndicate]]\n* [http://www.townhall.com/columnists/michellemalkin/archive.shtml Archive] of Malkin's columns at [[Townhall.com]]\n* [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2009/feb/19/columnist-isnt-smiling-over-swastika-in-rally/ \"Columnist isn't smiling over swastika in rally photo\"]. ''Rocky Mountain News''. February 19, 2009.\n* [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin112404.asp \"Michelle Malkin: Grace, gratitude, and G-d\"]. ''Jewish World Review''. November 24, 2004.\n* [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/michelle/malkin.archives.asp Archive of Malkin's columns] at ''[[Jewish World Review]]''\n* {{C-SPAN|michellemalkin}}\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20140328060105/http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/173558-1/Michelle+Malkin.aspx ''Booknotes'' interview with Malkin on ''Invasion'', December 8, 2002.]\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Malk ''In Depth'' interview with Malkin, January 3, 2010]\n\n{{Michelle Malkin}}\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malkin, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American polit