ok|last=Ortner|first=Vyola J.|title=You Can't Eat Dirt, Leading America's First All-Women Tribal Council and How We Changed Palm Springs|publisher=Fan Palm Research Project|isbn=978-0-615-49559-0|page=264 |author2=du Pont, Diana C. |year=2012|lccn=2011939660 | oclc=801995611 }}\n** {{cite book | last = Patencio | first = Chief Francisco |author2=Boynton, Margaret | title = Stories and Legends of the Palm Springs Indians | year = 1943 | location = Los Angeles | work = Times-Mirror | page = 33 | lccn = 44018350 | oclc = 4020904 }}\n** {{cite book| last=Ringwald |first=George|title=The Agua Caliente Indians and Their Guardians|location=Riverside, CA|publisher=Press-Enterprise|year=1968|page=36}} {{OCLC|3094608|14015139}} A reprint of Ringwald's Pulitzer Prize\u2013winning articles concerning the scandal of Section 14 of the Agua Caliente Indian Reservation.\n** {{cite book |last=Shaw |first=Rachel Dayton |title=Evolving Ecoscape: An Environmental and Cultural History of Palm Springs, California, and the Agua Caliente Indian Reservation, 1877\u20131939 |year=1999 |publisher=University of California (Ph.D. thesis) |location=San Diego, CA |page=374 |isbn=978-0-599-37980-0 |id={{ProQuest|304497715}} }} {{OCLC|41942987|43734890}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Palm Springs, California}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Palm Springs}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.visitpalmsprings.com/ Palm Springs Bureau of Tourism page]\n* [http://www.pspreservationfoundation.org/index.html Palm Springs Preservation Foundation]\n* {{curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Localities/P/Palm_Springs/|Palm Springs}}\n* {{cite web|title=Palm Springs, California|url=https://www.c-span.org/series/?citiesTour&city=774|publisher=[[C-SPAN]] Cities Tour|date=June 2013}}\n* [https://visitgreaterpalmsprings.com/ Greater Palm Springs Convention & Visitors Bureau]<!--\n* [http://www.palmspringsusa.com/ Palm Springs Convention & Visitors Authority website] Looks like spamlink, but has some indicia of officalness, therefore keeping for future reference--><!--\n* [http://www.palmspringshistoricalsociety.com/ Palm Springs Historical Society page] NOTE: does not link to the actual www.pshistoricalsociety.com page. Preserved with editor's comment for future reference-->\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Palm Springs\n|North = [[Morongo Valley]]<br />North Palm Springs\n|Northeast = [[Desert Hot Springs]]\n|East = [[Cathedral City, California|Cathedral City]]\n|Southeast = [[Rancho Mirage]]\n|South = ''[[Agua Caliente Band of Cahuilla Indians|Agua Caliente Indian Canyons]]''\n|Southwest = [[Idyllwild-Pine Cove]]<br />[[Mountain Center, California|Mountain Center]]<br />''[[San Jacinto Mountains]]''\n|West = ''[[Chino Canyon (California)|Chino Canyon]]''<br />''[[San Jacinto Mountains]]''\n|Northwest = [[Whitewater, California|Whitewater]]<br />[[Cabazon]]\n}}\n\n{{Inland Empire}}\n{{Riverside County, California}}\n{{Coachella Valley TV}}\n{{Palm Springs Radio}}\n{{American gay villages}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Palm Springs, California| ]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Cities in Riverside County, California]]\n[[Category:Coachella Valley]]\n[[Category:Gay villages in California]]\n[[Category:Incorporated cities and towns in California]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1896]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Colorado Desert]]\n[[Category:Sandboarding locations]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in California]]\n[[Category:Bradshaw Trail]]\n", "name_user": "TheAwesomeHwyh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Agua Caliente Casino\u2192Agua Caliente Casino Resort Spa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palm_Springs,_California"}
{"title_page": "Michael Xavier", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor and singer}}\n{{for|the alias of Magneto|Magneto (Marvel Comics)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Michael Xavier\n| birth_name  = Michael David Smith\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Actor]]<br />[[Singer]]\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present \n| website      = {{URL|michaelxavier.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Michael D. Xavier''' (born 27 November 1977) is an English [[actor]] and [[singer]].\n\n==Early life==\nXavier attended [[St. Francis Xavier's College (Liverpool)|St. Francis Xavier's College]] in [[Liverpool]], [[Knutsford High School]] in Cheshire, and ultimately completed his professional acting training at the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Chichester Festival Theatre - Michael Xavier|url=http://www.cft.org.uk/michael-xavier|website=www.cft.org.uk|publisher=Chichester Festival Theatre|accessdate=25 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141125152233/http://www.cft.org.uk/michael-xavier|archivedate=25 November 2014}}</ref> in 1999.  His first professional role was in the musical comedy ''Pageant'' at London's [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herbert|first1=I|title=Theatre Record|date=2000|publisher=I. Herbert|pages=614\u2013615|edition=Volume 20, Issues 9-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pageant Confirmed for West End Run|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/07-2000/pageant-confirmed-for-west-end-run-1-aug_30392.html|website=www.whatsonstage.com|publisher=WhatsonStage|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140616110840/http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/07-2000/pageant-confirmed-for-west-end-run-1-aug_30392.html|archivedate=16 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Work in theatre ==\n\nXavier has worked in lead roles on stage in the United Kingdom for 20 years. Notable productions in which he has appeared include ''[[Miss Saigon]]'', ''[[My Fair Lady]]'', [[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|''The Phantom of the Opera'']], [[Oklahoma (musical)|''Oklahoma!'']], and ''[[The Sound of Music]]''.  In 2014, he played Sid Sorokin opposite [[Joanna Riding]] in ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' at the [[Shaftesbury Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bosanquet|first1=Theo|title=Pajama Game confirms West End transfer, Michael Xavier and Joanna Riding star|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/chichester-theatre/news/12-2013/pajama-game-confirms-west-end-transfer-michael-xav_32985.html|website=www.whatsonstage.com|publisher=WhatsonStage|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Xavier played [[Rock Hudson]] in [[Tim Fountain]]'s play ''Rock'' at the [[Unity Theatre, Liverpool|Unity Theatre]] in Liverpool, the Library Theatre in Manchester, and the [[Oval House Theatre]] in London.  It went on to be produced as a radio play by production company Made in Manchester, and won the Best Online Only Audio Drama award at the [[BBC Audio Drama Awards]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Paul|title=The winners of the first BBC Audio Drama Awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/radio/2012/01/the_winners_of_the_first_bbc_a.html|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC Radio Blog|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rock Hudson radio drama wins BBC award|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/01/30/rock-hudson-radio-drama-wins-bbc-award/|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|publisher=Pink News|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nXavier has been nominated twice for a Laurence Olivier Award.  He was first nominated for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical]] in 2011 for his performance as Cinderella's Prince/Wolf in [[Into the Woods|''Into The Woods'']] at the [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Into the Woods wins 2011 Laurence Olivier Award|url=http://www.digitaltheatre.com/news/details/into-the-woods-wins-2011-laurence-olivier-award|website=www.digitaltheatre.com|accessdate=25 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310062950/http://www.digitaltheatre.com/news/details/into-the-woods-wins-2011-laurence-olivier-award|archivedate=10 March 2015}}</ref>  The same year he was also nominated for the [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]] for his performance as Oliver in the musical [[Love Story (musical)|''Love Story'']] at the [[Duchess Theatre]].<ref name=\"Love Story\">{{cite book|last1=Robertson|first1=Willie|title=Michael Ball - The Biography|publisher=John Blake|isbn=1857826744|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0a0CAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162&dq=michael+xavier+love+story&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FrR0VOjcNcrQ7Aaf44HQBA&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=michael%20xavier%20love%20story&f=false|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> In January 2017, Xavier's lead performance in \"[[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']]\" (at the London Coliseum) won the 2016 BroadwayWorld UK/West End Award for Best Actor in a New Production of a Musical.\n\n=== Major theatre credits ===\n{{MOSLOW|date=February 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Role !! Production !! Theatre !! Director\n|-\n| 2017 || Performer || [[Prince of Broadway (musical)|''Prince of Broadway'']] ||  [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] || [[Hal Prince]], [[Susan Stroman]]\n|-\n|2017\n|Joe Gillis\n|[[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']]\n|[[Palace Theatre (New York City)|Palace Theatre]]\n|[[Lonny Price]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Archibald Craven || [[The Secret Garden (musical)|''The Secret Garden'']] ||  [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]] || David Armstrong\n|-\n| 2016 || Joe Gillis || [[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']] || [[London Coliseum|London Colliseum]] ([[English National Opera]]) || [[Lonny Price]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Hookbeard || ''[[Bumblescratch]]'' || [[Adelphi Theatre]] || [[Stewart Nicholls]]\n|-\n|2015\n|Gaylord\n|''[[Show Boat|Showboat]]''\n|[[Sheffield Theatres|Sheffield Crucible]]\n|[[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]]\n|-\n| 2015 || Suffolk / George of Clarence || [[The Wars of the Roses (adaptation)|''The War of the Roses'']] || [[Rose Theatre, Kingston|Rose Theatre Kingston]] || [[Trevor Nunn]]\n|-\n| 2015 || John Wilkes Booth || [[Assassins (musical)|''Assassins'']] || [[Menier Chocolate Factory]] || [[Jamie Lloyd (director)|Jamie Lloyd]]\n|-\n| 2014 || Sid Sorokin || ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' || [[Shaftesbury Theatre]] || [[Richard Eyre]]\n|-\n| 2013 || Captain Von Trapp || ''[[The Sound of Music]]'' || [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]] || Rachel Kavanagh\n|-\n| 2012 || James Prince || ''[[Soho Cinders]]''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shenton|first1=Mark|title=Soho Cinders to Premiere at London's Soho Theatre, With Cast Led by Jenna Russell and Michael Xavier|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/soho-cinders-to-premiere-at-londons-soho-theatre-with-cast-led-by-jenna-rus-193723|website=www.playbill.com|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> || [[Soho Theatre]] || [[Jonathan Butterell]]\n|-\n| 2012 || Bob Baker || ''[[Wonderful Town]]'' || UK No. 1 Tour || Braham Murray\n|-\n| 2012 || Cornelius Hackl || [[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|''Hello Dolly'']] || [[Curve Theatre, Leicester|Curve Theatre Leicester]] || Paul Kerryson\n|-\n| 2010 || Oliver || [[Love Story (musical)|''Love Story'']] || [[Duchess Theatre]] || Rachel Kavanagh\n|-\n| 2010 || Wolf / Cinderella's Prince || ''[[Into The Woods]]'' || [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]] || Timothy Sheader\n|-\n| 2009 || Curly || [[Oklahoma (musical)|''Oklahoma!'']] || [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] || John Doyle\n|-\n| 2008 || Rock Hudson || ''Rock'' || [[Oval House Theatre]] || Tamara Harvey\n|-\n| 2006 || Raoul || [[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|''The Phantom of the Opera'']] || [[Her Majesty's Theatre]] || Hal Prince\n|-\n|2004\n|Artie Green\n|''Sunset Boulevard''\n|[[Cork Opera House]], [[Ireland]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004 || Sky || ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'' || International Tour || [[Phyllida Lloyd]] / Paul Garrington\n|-\n| 2003 || Freddy Eynsford-Hill || ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' || [[Theatre Royal Drury Lane]] || [[Trevor Nunn]]\n|-\n| 2003 || Christopher Scott (Alternate/Cover) || ''[[Miss Saigon]]'' || UK Tour || Matthew Ryan\n|-\n| 2000 || Miss Great Plains || ''Pageant'' || [[Vaudeville Theatre]] || [[Bill Russell (lyricist)|Bill Russell]]\n|}\n\n== Presenting, recording, and film work ==\n\nIn 2013, Xavier co-presented the [[Olivier Awards]] [[BBC Radio 2]] Covent Garden Stage with [[Claudia Winkleman]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Claudia Winkleman & Michael Xavier to host the BBC Radio 2 Stage during Olivier Awards|url=http://www.westendframe.com/2013/04/ClaudiaWinkleman-MichaelXavier-tohostBBCRadio2Stage.html|website=www.westendframe.com|publisher=West End Frame|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> and returned again in 2014 to co-present on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] Stage with [[Myleene Klass]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Olivier Awards 2014|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/awards/|website=www.olivierawards.com|publisher=Olivier Awards|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218191415/http://www.olivierawards.com/awards/|archivedate=18 December 2014}}</ref> He also hosted the UK Theatre Awards at the historic [[Guildhall]] in the [[City of London]] in both 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners of 2013 UK Theatre Awards Announced|url=http://www.uktheatre.org/newsandpress/article.aspx?article=566|website=www.uktheatre.org|publisher=UK Theatre|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UK Theatre Awards 2014 - Winners Announced|url=http://www.uktheatre.org/theatreawardsuk.aspx|website=www.uktheatre.org|publisher=UK Theatre|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nXavier's film work includes his portrayal of Tom in the 2014 production ''Never Let Go'' with director Howard J Ford for Latitude Films, scheduled for release in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howard J Ford\u2019s Never Let Go enters post production|url=http://www.liveforfilms.com/2014/12/03/howard-j-fords-never-let-go-enters-post-production/|website=www.liveforfilm.com|publisher=Live For Films|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>  In 2013, he appeared as Rob in the short film ''Gnomeland'' by writer/director [[Francesca Jaynes]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Gnomeland - Cast|url=http://www.gnomelandthefilm.com/cast-and-crew/cast/|website=www.gnomelandthefilm.com|publisher=For George Films|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141209170741/http://www.gnomelandthefilm.com/cast-and-crew/cast/|archivedate=9 December 2014}}</ref> as well as playing a Russian Gulag Prisoner in [[Walt Disney Pictures]]' ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]'', filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]].\n\nIn addition, Xavier has worked as a recording artist, with both radio and original soundtrack credits to his name. In 2007, [[BBC Radio 2]] presented a special edition of ''[[Friday Night is Music Night]]'', celebrating the work of [[Leonard Bernstein]] and the 50th anniversary of ''[[West Side Story]]''. [[Paul Gambaccini]] presented the program at London's [[Mermaid Theatre]], featuring the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]] and Xavier as Tony.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Night is Music Night|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007z6ty|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hemley|first1=Matthew|title=Radio 2 marks 50 years of West Side Story|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2007/09/radio-2-marks-50-years-of-west-side-story/|website=www.thestage.co.uk|publisher=The Stage|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> He also played Artie Green in the [[BBC Radio 2]] live recording of [[Sunset Boulevard]], performed at the [[Cork Opera House]] with [[Michael Ball (singer)|Michael Ball]] and [[Petula Clark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunset Boulevard - Cork Concert Revival 2014|url=http://www.ovrtur.com/production/2893901/credits|website=www.ovrtur.com|publisher=Ovrtur|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> Outside of radio, his work in recordings includes ''[[Bumblescratch]]'' (2016 London Concert Cast Recording) ''Collaborations: The Songs of [[Elliot Davis (composer)|Elliot Davis]]'' (2013), ''Lift'' (2012 Concept Album), ''[[Soho Cinders]]'' (2011 Concert Cast), ''Love Story'' (2011 Original London Cast), and ''Little Women'' (2004 Studio Cast).<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Xavier Discography|url=http://castalbums.org/people/Michael-Xavier/36641|website=www.castalbums.org|publisher=CastAlbums|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== MX Masterclass ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=April 2017}}\nXavier is the Principal of [https://mxmasterclass.com MX Masterclass], a training school for musical theatre students which aims to aid them in gaining acceptance to professional training colleges. The school runs every Sunday, based at The Umbrella Rooms in the West End. Their patron is [[Matthew Bourne]]. Regular teachers over the years have included Anna Tringham, Ross Sharkey, Lucinda Lawrence, Brandon Lee Sears, Nicola Coates, [[Peter Polycarpou]] and [[Alex Young (musical theatre)|Alex Young]]. Students are also taught by guest performers and practitioners including [[Kerry Ellis]], [[Ramin Karimloo]], [[Rebecca Trehearn]], Marc Antolin, [[Robbie Sherman]], [[Katie Brayben]], [[Louise Dearman]], Trevor Dion Nicholas and [[Matt Henry (singer)]]. The students are often given an opportunity to perform at various charity and West End events at which Xavier also appears. The students also appear at a Christmas concert at [[St Paul's, Covent Garden]], alongside industry professionals. The 2016 concert was hosted by [[Rufus Hound]]. \nStudents have many performance opportunities throughout the year and gain national and local news coverage in the process. Last year they performed at The Best Of The West End concert at [[The Royal Albert Hall]] starring many big West End names including Xavier himself.<ref name=\"The Newsroom\">{{cite web |last1=Jeffrey |first1=Isabella |title=Isabella Takes To The Royal Albert Hall Stage |url=https://www.morpethherald.co.uk/news/isabella-takes-to-the-royal-albert-hall-stage-238204 |website=morpethherald.co.uk |publisher=Morpeth Herald |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\nThey have also performed at Lambert Jackson Productions concert, West End Women <ref name=\"Lambert Jackson Productions\">{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Lambert |title=West End Women |url=https://www.lambertjackson.co.uk/west-end-women/ |website=lambertjackson.co.uk |publisher=Lambert Jackson |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> and Main Men Of Musicals <ref name=\"Greg Stewart\">{{cite web |last1=Weekly |first1=Theatre |title=Main Men Of Musicals concert |url=https://theatreweekly.com/review-main-men-of-musicals-at-cadogan-hall/ |website=theatreweekly.com |publisher=theatreweekly.com |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.michaelxavier.co.uk Official Website]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2440625 IMDB]\n* {{IBDB name|511402}}\n* [https://www.stagefaves.com/performers/michael-xavier/]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xavier, Michael}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor and singer}}\n{{for|the alias of Magneto|Magneto (Marvel Comics)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Michael Xavier\n| birth_name  = Michael David Smith\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Actor]]<br />[[Singer]]\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present \n| website      = {{URL|michaelxavier.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Michael D. Xavier''' (born 27 November 1977) is an English [[actor]] and [[singer]].\n\n==Early life==\nXavier attended [[St. Francis Xavier's College (Liverpool)|St. Francis Xavier's College]] in [[Liverpool]], [[Knutsford High School]] in Cheshire, and ultimately completed his professional acting training at the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Chichester Festival Theatre - Michael Xavier|url=http://www.cft.org.uk/michael-xavier|website=www.cft.org.uk|publisher=Chichester Festival Theatre|accessdate=25 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141125152233/http://www.cft.org.uk/michael-xavier|archivedate=25 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in 1999.  His first professional role was in the musical comedy ''Pageant'' at London's [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herbert|first1=I|title=Theatre Record|date=2000|publisher=I. Herbert|pages=614\u2013615|edition=Volume 20, Issues 9-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pageant Confirmed for West End Run|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/07-2000/pageant-confirmed-for-west-end-run-1-aug_30392.html|website=www.whatsonstage.com|publisher=WhatsonStage|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140616110840/http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/07-2000/pageant-confirmed-for-west-end-run-1-aug_30392.html|archivedate=16 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Work in theatre ==\n\nXavier has worked in lead roles on stage in the United Kingdom for 20 years. Notable productions in which he has appeared include ''[[Miss Saigon]]'', ''[[My Fair Lady]]'', [[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|''The Phantom of the Opera'']], [[Oklahoma (musical)|''Oklahoma!'']], and ''[[The Sound of Music]]''.  In 2014, he played Sid Sorokin opposite [[Joanna Riding]] in ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' at the [[Shaftesbury Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bosanquet|first1=Theo|title=Pajama Game confirms West End transfer, Michael Xavier and Joanna Riding star|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/chichester-theatre/news/12-2013/pajama-game-confirms-west-end-transfer-michael-xav_32985.html|website=www.whatsonstage.com|publisher=WhatsonStage|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Xavier played [[Rock Hudson]] in [[Tim Fountain]]'s play ''Rock'' at the [[Unity Theatre, Liverpool|Unity Theatre]] in Liverpool, the Library Theatre in Manchester, and the [[Oval House Theatre]] in London.  It went on to be produced as a radio play by production company Made in Manchester, and won the Best Online Only Audio Drama award at the [[BBC Audio Drama Awards]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Paul|title=The winners of the first BBC Audio Drama Awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/radio/2012/01/the_winners_of_the_first_bbc_a.html|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC Radio Blog|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rock Hudson radio drama wins BBC award|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/01/30/rock-hudson-radio-drama-wins-bbc-award/|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|publisher=Pink News|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nXavier has been nominated twice for a Laurence Olivier Award.  He was first nominated for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical]] in 2011 for his performance as Cinderella's Prince/Wolf in [[Into the Woods|''Into The Woods'']] at the [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Into the Woods wins 2011 Laurence Olivier Award|url=http://www.digitaltheatre.com/news/details/into-the-woods-wins-2011-laurence-olivier-award|website=www.digitaltheatre.com|accessdate=25 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310062950/http://www.digitaltheatre.com/news/details/into-the-woods-wins-2011-laurence-olivier-award|archivedate=10 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The same year he was also nominated for the [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]] for his performance as Oliver in the musical [[Love Story (musical)|''Love Story'']] at the [[Duchess Theatre]].<ref name=\"Love Story\">{{cite book|last1=Robertson|first1=Willie|title=Michael Ball - The Biography|publisher=John Blake|isbn=1857826744|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0a0CAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162&dq=michael+xavier+love+story&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FrR0VOjcNcrQ7Aaf44HQBA&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=michael%20xavier%20love%20story&f=false|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> In January 2017, Xavier's lead performance in \"[[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']]\" (at the London Coliseum) won the 2016 BroadwayWorld UK/West End Award for Best Actor in a New Production of a Musical.\n\n=== Major theatre credits ===\n{{MOSLOW|date=February 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Role !! Production !! Theatre !! Director\n|-\n| 2017 || Performer || [[Prince of Broadway (musical)|''Prince of Broadway'']] ||  [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] || [[Hal Prince]], [[Susan Stroman]]\n|-\n|2017\n|Joe Gillis\n|[[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']]\n|[[Palace Theatre (New York City)|Palace Theatre]]\n|[[Lonny Price]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Archibald Craven || [[The Secret Garden (musical)|''The Secret Garden'']] ||  [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]] || David Armstrong\n|-\n| 2016 || Joe Gillis || [[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|''Sunset Boulevard'']] || [[London Coliseum|London Colliseum]] ([[English National Opera]]) || [[Lonny Price]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Hookbeard || ''[[Bumblescratch]]'' || [[Adelphi Theatre]] || [[Stewart Nicholls]]\n|-\n|2015\n|Gaylord\n|''[[Show Boat|Showboat]]''\n|[[Sheffield Theatres|Sheffield Crucible]]\n|[[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]]\n|-\n| 2015 || Suffolk / George of Clarence || [[The Wars of the Roses (adaptation)|''The War of the Roses'']] || [[Rose Theatre, Kingston|Rose Theatre Kingston]] || [[Trevor Nunn]]\n|-\n| 2015 || John Wilkes Booth || [[Assassins (musical)|''Assassins'']] || [[Menier Chocolate Factory]] || [[Jamie Lloyd (director)|Jamie Lloyd]]\n|-\n| 2014 || Sid Sorokin || ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' || [[Shaftesbury Theatre]] || [[Richard Eyre]]\n|-\n| 2013 || Captain Von Trapp || ''[[The Sound of Music]]'' || [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]] || Rachel Kavanagh\n|-\n| 2012 || James Prince || ''[[Soho Cinders]]''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shenton|first1=Mark|title=Soho Cinders to Premiere at London's Soho Theatre, With Cast Led by Jenna Russell and Michael Xavier|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/soho-cinders-to-premiere-at-londons-soho-theatre-with-cast-led-by-jenna-rus-193723|website=www.playbill.com|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> || [[Soho Theatre]] || [[Jonathan Butterell]]\n|-\n| 2012 || Bob Baker || ''[[Wonderful Town]]'' || UK No. 1 Tour || Braham Murray\n|-\n| 2012 || Cornelius Hackl || [[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|''Hello Dolly'']] || [[Curve Theatre, Leicester|Curve Theatre Leicester]] || Paul Kerryson\n|-\n| 2010 || Oliver || [[Love Story (musical)|''Love Story'']] || [[Duchess Theatre]] || Rachel Kavanagh\n|-\n| 2010 || Wolf / Cinderella's Prince || ''[[Into The Woods]]'' || [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre]] || Timothy Sheader\n|-\n| 2009 || Curly || [[Oklahoma (musical)|''Oklahoma!'']] || [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] || John Doyle\n|-\n| 2008 || Rock Hudson || ''Rock'' || [[Oval House Theatre]] || Tamara Harvey\n|-\n| 2006 || Raoul || [[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|''The Phantom of the Opera'']] || [[Her Majesty's Theatre]] || Hal Prince\n|-\n|2004\n|Artie Green\n|''Sunset Boulevard''\n|[[Cork Opera House]], [[Ireland]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004 || Sky || ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'' || International Tour || [[Phyllida Lloyd]] / Paul Garrington\n|-\n| 2003 || Freddy Eynsford-Hill || ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' || [[Theatre Royal Drury Lane]] || [[Trevor Nunn]]\n|-\n| 2003 || Christopher Scott (Alternate/Cover) || ''[[Miss Saigon]]'' || UK Tour || Matthew Ryan\n|-\n| 2000 || Miss Great Plains || ''Pageant'' || [[Vaudeville Theatre]] || [[Bill Russell (lyricist)|Bill Russell]]\n|}\n\n== Presenting, recording, and film work ==\n\nIn 2013, Xavier co-presented the [[Olivier Awards]] [[BBC Radio 2]] Covent Garden Stage with [[Claudia Winkleman]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Claudia Winkleman & Michael Xavier to host the BBC Radio 2 Stage during Olivier Awards|url=http://www.westendframe.com/2013/04/ClaudiaWinkleman-MichaelXavier-tohostBBCRadio2Stage.html|website=www.westendframe.com|publisher=West End Frame|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> and returned again in 2014 to co-present on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] Stage with [[Myleene Klass]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Olivier Awards 2014|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/awards/|website=www.olivierawards.com|publisher=Olivier Awards|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218191415/http://www.olivierawards.com/awards/|archivedate=18 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also hosted the UK Theatre Awards at the historic [[Guildhall]] in the [[City of London]] in both 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners of 2013 UK Theatre Awards Announced|url=http://www.uktheatre.org/newsandpress/article.aspx?article=566|website=www.uktheatre.org|publisher=UK Theatre|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UK Theatre Awards 2014 - Winners Announced|url=http://www.uktheatre.org/theatreawardsuk.aspx|website=www.uktheatre.org|publisher=UK Theatre|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nXavier's film work includes his portrayal of Tom in the 2014 production ''Never Let Go'' with director Howard J Ford for Latitude Films, scheduled for release in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howard J Ford\u2019s Never Let Go enters post production|url=http://www.liveforfilms.com/2014/12/03/howard-j-fords-never-let-go-enters-post-production/|website=www.liveforfilm.com|publisher=Live For Films|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>  In 2013, he appeared as Rob in the short film ''Gnomeland'' by writer/director [[Francesca Jaynes]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Gnomeland - Cast|url=http://www.gnomelandthefilm.com/cast-and-crew/cast/|website=www.gnomelandthefilm.com|publisher=For George Films|accessdate=9 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141209170741/http://www.gnomelandthefilm.com/cast-and-crew/cast/|archivedate=9 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as well as playing a Russian Gulag Prisoner in [[Walt Disney Pictures]]' ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]'', filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]].\n\nIn addition, Xavier has worked as a recording artist, with both radio and original soundtrack credits to his name. In 2007, [[BBC Radio 2]] presented a special edition of ''[[Friday Night is Music Night]]'', celebrating the work of [[Leonard Bernstein]] and the 50th anniversary of ''[[West Side Story]]''. [[Paul Gambaccini]] presented the program at London's [[Mermaid Theatre]], featuring the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]] and Xavier as Tony.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Night is Music Night|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007z6ty|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hemley|first1=Matthew|title=Radio 2 marks 50 years of West Side Story|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2007/09/radio-2-marks-50-years-of-west-side-story/|website=www.thestage.co.uk|publisher=The Stage|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> He also played Artie Green in the [[BBC Radio 2]] live recording of [[Sunset Boulevard]], performed at the [[Cork Opera House]] with [[Michael Ball (singer)|Michael Ball]] and [[Petula Clark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunset Boulevard - Cork Concert Revival 2014|url=http://www.ovrtur.com/production/2893901/credits|website=www.ovrtur.com|publisher=Ovrtur|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> Outside of radio, his work in recordings includes ''[[Bumblescratch]]'' (2016 London Concert Cast Recording) ''Collaborations: The Songs of [[Elliot Davis (composer)|Elliot Davis]]'' (2013), ''Lift'' (2012 Concept Album), ''[[Soho Cinders]]'' (2011 Concert Cast), ''Love Story'' (2011 Original London Cast), and ''Little Women'' (2004 Studio Cast).<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Xavier Discography|url=http://castalbums.org/people/Michael-Xavier/36641|website=www.castalbums.org|publisher=CastAlbums|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== MX Masterclass ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=April 2017}}\nXavier is the Principal of [https://mxmasterclass.com MX Masterclass], a training school for musical theatre students which aims to aid them in gaining acceptance to professional training colleges. The school runs every Sunday, based at The Umbrella Rooms in the West End. Their patron is [[Matthew Bourne]]. Regular teachers over the years have included Anna Tringham, Ross Sharkey, Lucinda Lawrence, Brandon Lee Sears, Nicola Coates, [[Peter Polycarpou]] and [[Alex Young (musical theatre)|Alex Young]]. Students are also taught by guest performers and practitioners including [[Kerry Ellis]], [[Ramin Karimloo]], [[Rebecca Trehearn]], Marc Antolin, [[Robbie Sherman]], [[Katie Brayben]], [[Louise Dearman]], Trevor Dion Nicholas and [[Matt Henry (singer)]]. The students are often given an opportunity to perform at various charity and West End events at which Xavier also appears. The students also appear at a Christmas concert at [[St Paul's, Covent Garden]], alongside industry professionals. The 2016 concert was hosted by [[Rufus Hound]]. \nStudents have many performance opportunities throughout the year and gain national and local news coverage in the process. Last year they performed at The Best Of The West End concert at [[The Royal Albert Hall]] starring many big West End names including Xavier himself.<ref name=\"The Newsroom\">{{cite web |last1=Jeffrey |first1=Isabella |title=Isabella Takes To The Royal Albert Hall Stage |url=https://www.morpethherald.co.uk/news/isabella-takes-to-the-royal-albert-hall-stage-238204 |website=morpethherald.co.uk |publisher=Morpeth Herald |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\nThey have also performed at Lambert Jackson Productions concert, West End Women <ref name=\"Lambert Jackson Productions\">{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Lambert |title=West End Women |url=https://www.lambertjackson.co.uk/west-end-women/ |website=lambertjackson.co.uk |publisher=Lambert Jackson |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> and Main Men Of Musicals <ref name=\"Greg Stewart\">{{cite web |last1=Weekly |first1=Theatre |title=Main Men Of Musicals concert |url=https://theatreweekly.com/review-main-men-of-musicals-at-cadogan-hall/ |website=theatreweekly.com |publisher=theatreweekly.com |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.michaelxavier.co.uk Official Website]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2440625 IMDB]\n* {{IBDB name|511402}}\n* [https://www.stagefaves.com/performers/michael-xavier/]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xavier, Michael}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Xavier"}
{"title_page": "Alberto Sordi", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Alberto Sordi\n| image         = Alberto Sordi (1962).tif\n| caption       = Sordi in 1962\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1920|6|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rome]], Italy\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2003|2|24|1920|6|15}}\n| death_place   = [[Rome]], Italy\n| other_names   = Albertone\n| yearsactive   = 1937\u20131998\n| occupation = Actor, voice actor, singer, director, screenwriter\n|height= {{convert|1.75|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| website       = {{url|albertosordi.it}}\n}}\n'''Alberto Sordi''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Italian orders of merit|Cavaliere di Gran Croce OMRI]]}} (June 15, 1920 \u2013 February 24, 2003) was an Italian actor, voice actor, singer, director and screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/voci/vociasor.htm |title=Alberto Sordi's dubbing contributions|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/DettaglioDecorato.asp?idprogressivo=11640&iddecorato=11220|title=Il sito ufficiale della Presidenza della Repubblica|first=Segretariato generale della Presidenza della Repubblica \u2013 Servizio sistemi|last=informatici|accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Rome to a schoolteacher and a musician, Sordi enrolled in [[Milan]]'s [[Accademia dei Filodrammatici|dramatic arts academy]] but was kicked out because of his thick [[Romanesco dialect|Roman]] accent. In the meantime he studied to be an opera singer, a [[bass (voice)|bass]]. It was his accent and voice that would later prove to be his trademark.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Alberto Sordi and Lea Padovani 1954.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sordi and [[Lea Padovani]] in ''[[Il seduttore]]'' (1954)]]\nIn a career that spanned seven decades, Sordi<ref>{{cite web |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=yBP39oBztlcC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=alberto+sordi+actor&source=bl&ots=8RIuAuaLmV&sig=aqJ1u4OylReQ7KdL2koCyO1WXjU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjz8r-IvJ_aAhXh4IMKHX6yBtA4RhDoAQg5MAM#v=onepage&q=alberto%20sordi%20actor&f=false|title =\nThe Richard Burton Diaries|accessdate = 3 April 2018 }}</ref> established himself as an icon<ref>{{cite web |url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/alberto-sordi-36300.html|title =Alberto Sordi comic icon of Italian cinema|accessdate = 3 April 2018 }}</ref> of Italian cinema with his representative skills at both comedy and light drama. His movie career began in the late 1930s with bit parts and secondary characters in wartime movies. After the war he began working as a dubber for the Italian versions of [[Laurel and Hardy]] shorts, voicing [[Oliver Hardy]]. Early roles included Fellini's'' [[The White Sheik]] ''in 1952, Fellini's ''[[I vitelloni]] ''(1953), a movie about young slackers, in which he plays a weak, effeminate immature loafer and a starring role in ''[[The Bachelor (1955 film)|The Bachelor]]'' playing a single man trying to find love. In 1959 he appeared in Monicelli's ''[[The Great War (1959 film)|Great War]]'', considered by many critics and film historians to be one of the best Italian comedies. The Hollywood Foreign Press recognized his abilities when he was awarded a Golden Globe for Best Motion Picture Actor in a Musical or Comedy for ''[[To bed or not to bed]]'' (1963). Sordi acted alongside Britain's [[David Niven]] in the [[World War II]] comedy ''[[The Best of Enemies (1961 film)|The Best of Enemies]]'' and in 1965 he was in another highly regarded comedy, ''[[I complessi]]'' (''Complexes'').\n\nIn 1969 he was a member of the jury at the [[6th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1969\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1969 |title=6th Moscow International Film Festival (1969) |accessdate=17 December 2012 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116194825/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1969 |archivedate=January 16, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nSordi also succeeded in dramatic roles, most notably in 1977's ''[[Un borghese piccolo piccolo]]'' (''An Average Little Man'') in which he portrays an elderly civil servant whose son is killed in an armed robbery, and sets out to exact revenge.\n\nIn 1984, he directed and co-scripted ''Tutti dentro'' (''Off to jail, everybody''), in which he played a judge who has warrants for corruption served on ministers and businessmen.\nAlberto Sordi<ref>{{cite web |url =https://www.britannica.com/biography/Alberto-Sordi|title =\nItalian actor Alberto Sordi|accessdate = 3 April 2018 }}</ref> was really masterful in two broad roles: one being the one of the underdog, militating against injustices and prevarications, the other that of the prevaricator himself.\nOne has only to watch his performances as the returning emigrant unjustly convicted in ''[[Detenuto in attesa di giudizio]]'' or the miserly sub-proletarian of ''[[Lo scopone scientifico]]'' teased by the old millionaire [[Bette Davis]] into endless card games where he hopes to find release from his poverty to appreciate his skills in the first role, while the rampant, unscrupulous doctor he plays in ''[[Il medico della mutua]] ''is the perfect example of his aptness at rendering characters who were both truly despicable and completely believable. In 1985, he was a member of the jury at the [[35th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale 1985\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1985/04_jury_1985/04_Jury_1985.html |title=Berlinale: Juries |accessdate=8 January 2011 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nSordi died shortly before his eighty-third birthday following a heart attack. A crowd in excess of a million gathered to pay their last respects at his funeral by the [[Basilica of St. John Lateran]], the largest of such event ever attended in Rome, second only to that of [[Pope John Paul II]] who died two years later.\nSordi was also a big supporter of [[AS Roma]] football team.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Actor===\n{{div col}}\n[[File:SottoilsolediRoma-1948-Sordi.png|thumbnail|Sordi in ''[[Under the Sun of Rome]]'' (1948)]]\n* ''[[Scipio Africanus: The Defeat of Hannibal|Scipione l'africano]]'' (1937) as Comparsa soldato romano\n* ''[[The Ferocious Saladin]]'' (1937) as The Lion\n* ''[[Princess Tarakanova (1938 film)|Princess Tarakanova]]'' (1938) as Ciaruskin (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Night of Tricks]]'' (1939) as Bentivoglio\n* ''[[Cuori nella tormenta]]'' (1940) as Giulio Ferri\n* ''Il bravo di Venezia'' (1941)\n* ''[[Le signorine della villa accanto]]'' (1941) as Un giovane invitato al ballo\n* ''[[Giarabub]]'' (1942) as Il tenente Sordi\n* ''[[The Three Pilots]]'' (1942) as Filippo Nardini\n* ''[[La signorina]]'' (1942) as Nino\n* ''[[After Casanova's Fashion]]'' (1942) as Un giocatore di biliardo\n* ''[[Sant'Elena piccola isola]]'' (1943) as Il capitano Popleton\n* ''[[Tre ragazze cercano marito]]'' (1944) as Giulio\n* ''[[The Za-Bum Circus]]'' (1944) (segment \"Galop finale al circo\")\n* ''[[Chi l'ha visto?]]'' (1945) as Un idraulico\n* ''[[The Innocent Casimiro]]'' (1945) as Guido Corra\n* ''[[His Young Wife]]'' (1945) as Camillo Barbarotti\n* ''[[Il vento m'ha cantato una canzone]]'' (1947) as Paolo\n* ''[[Flesh Will Surrender]]'' (1947) as Doberti\n* ''[[Il Passatore (film)|Il Passatore]]'' (1947) as The Boyfriend\n* ''[[Under the Sun of Rome]]'' (1948) as Fernando\n* ''[[Che tempi!]]'' (1948) as Manuel Aguirre\n* ''[[Cameriera bella presenza offresi...]]'' (1951) as Donato\n* ''[[Mamma mia, che impressione!]]'' (1951) as Alberto\n* ''[[Viva il cinema!]]'' (1952) as Narratore (voice)\n* ''[[The White Sheik]]'' (1952) as Fernando Rivoli \u2013 The White Sheik\n* ''[[Toto and the King of Rome]]'' (1952) as Il maestro elementare\n* ''Giovinezza'' (1952)\n* ''[[The Piano Tuner Has Arrived]]'' (1952) as Avvocato Adolfo\n* ''[